WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.960
[Amit Varma]: If there is one thing that is certain in this world, it is that I am a disgrace to Warsaw.

00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:17.480
[Amit Varma]: I've lived in this most filmy suburb of Mumbai for the last 15 years and have been here throughout

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:20.840
[Unknown]: the 189 weeks that the scene and the unseen has been running.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:26.560
[Amit Varma]: I've recorded episodes on economics, public policy, political philosophy, history, sociology,

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:32.880
[Amit Varma]: and sports, but not a single episode on cinema, not a single episode on entertainment, not

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:37.320
[Unknown]: a single episode on acting or direction or cinematography, or even music.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:43.480
[Amit Varma]: And I say in Warsaw, this is an unpardonable, unspeakable, eldritch, monstrous omission,

00:00:43.480 --> 00:00:50.840
[Unknown]: and it will be too late for redemption if I don't do something right now.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:56.680
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:00:56.680 --> 00:00:57.680
[Unknown]: science.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:03.360
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:04.680
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:07.200
[Amit Varma]: In one sense, you could say that we are all actors.

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:11.560
[Amit Varma]: We are often performing for others and always performing for ourselves.

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:15.960
[Unknown]: Today's episode is about acting, but not acting in this deep metaphysical sense, which may

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:18.880
[Unknown]: or may not be me acting profound to myself.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:23.920
[Amit Varma]: Instead, my guests today are two wonderful actors who have made a name for themselves

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:27.440
[Amit Varma]: doing independent cinema and cutting edge web series.

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:30.080
[Amit Varma]: These are exciting times in Indian entertainment.

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:34.440
[Amit Varma]: And these two are both living their dream and paying their dues.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:38.840
[Amit Varma]: Being an actor in Mumbai can be turbulent, but so many different worlds and sensibilities

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:40.840
[Amit Varma]: colliding with each other.

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:45.560
[Amit Varma]: Jessica Duggal studied mathematics in college, became a researcher and wonk for a while,

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:49.480
[Amit Varma]: but then fell in love with acting and decided that was all she wanted to do.

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:54.400
[Amit Varma]: She's acted in films like Kissa, Manto, and Lootcase, as also in web series like Delhi

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:58.520
[Amit Varma]: Crime, Made in Heaven, Mirzapur, and A Suitable Boy.

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:02.920
[Amit Varma]: Her husband Mukul Chadha also studied math in college, though not with Rasika, and did

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:05.440
[Unknown]: an MBA from IIM Ahmedabad.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:11.040
[Amit Varma]: He then became a banker in New York and single handedly caused the 2008 financial crisis.

00:02:11.040 --> 00:02:12.880
[Amit Varma]: He then gave it up to become an actor.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:17.920
[Amit Varma]: His most recent part was a lead role in the Indian version of The Office.

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:22.800
[Amit Varma]: He has also acted a fair bit in independent cinema and does improv theater in Mumbai as

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:23.800
[Amit Varma]: well.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:28.400
[Amit Varma]: Mukul and I were both serious poker players once upon a time, which is how we became friends.

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:33.160
[Amit Varma]: I'd been thinking for a while of inviting Mukul and Rasika onto the show to talk about

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.320
[Amit Varma]: their journeys, the state of Indian cinema, and the craft of acting.

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:39.880
[Amit Varma]: I love the conversation we ended up having.

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:44.640
[Amit Varma]: But before we get to it, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:48.200
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Scene and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:49.480
[Amit Varma]: show alive.

00:02:49.480 --> 00:02:52.520
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and the Unseen has been a labor of love for me.

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:58.120
[Amit Varma]: I've enjoyed putting together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe,

00:02:58.120 --> 00:02:59.120
[Amit Varma]: and hopefully yours as well.

00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:04.440
[Amit Varma]: But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off the show.

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:08.440
[Amit Varma]: Although The Scene and the Unseen has great numbers, advertisers haven't really woken

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:11.440
[Amit Varma]: up to the insane engagement level of podcasts.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:15.840
[Amit Varma]: And I do many, many hours of deep research for each episode, besides all the logistics

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:22.000
[Amit Varma]: of producing the show myself, scheduling guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:23.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.340
[Amit Varma]: So, well, I'm trying a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves you.

00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:29.560
[Amit Varma]: My proposition for you is this.

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:34.400
[Amit Varma]: For every episode of The Scene and the Unseen that you enjoy, buy me a cup of coffee, or

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:37.200
[Amit Varma]: even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth.

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:43.120
[Amit Varma]: You can do this by heading over to sceneunseen.in slash support and contributing an amount of

00:03:43.120 --> 00:03:44.120
[Amit Varma]: your choice.

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:46.080
[Amit Varma]: This is not a subscription.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:53.120
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and the Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps and at sceneunseen.in.

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:55.720
[Amit Varma]: This is just a gesture of appreciation.

00:03:55.720 --> 00:04:00.560
[Amit Varma]: Help keep this thing going sceneunseen.in slash support.

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:05.800
[Amit Varma]: Rasika and Mukul, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:08.080
[Guest 2]: Well, thank you for having us, Amit.

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:09.080
[Guest 2]: Thank you.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:14.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, before we start talking about your acting careers, which sort of and about the

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:20.000
[Amit Varma]: craft itself and Indian cinema and all of that, I'm very curious to sort of know about

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:21.640
[Amit Varma]: your personal backgrounds.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:25.160
[Amit Varma]: And I'll start with Mukul first, because Mukul, I don't know if you remember, but and this

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:29.400
[Amit Varma]: almost sounds now that I realize it, it almost sounds creepy, but I kind of remember the

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:35.080
[Amit Varma]: exact time when we met, which was in March or April 2007, where a mutual friend of ours,

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Manish Vij, the great Sepia Mutiny blogger, he'd lived in Bombay for a few years, and

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:43.760
[Amit Varma]: he was moving back to the States and he had a farewell party in some Bandra nightclub

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:45.120
[Amit Varma]: and you dropped in for a while.

00:04:45.120 --> 00:04:49.320
[Amit Varma]: And I was introduced to you and told that this is Mukul Chaddha, the actor.

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:53.160
[Amit Varma]: What I kind of noticed about your career is, you know, people often accuse me of having

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:57.760
[Amit Varma]: had an interesting life in just in terms of CV, because, you know, in the 90s, there is

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:02.920
[Amit Varma]: all the MTV and Channel V. And then there is in the 40s, there is a sort of journalism

00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:07.240
[Amit Varma]: and the blogging and everything and then there's five years as a professional poker player,

00:05:07.240 --> 00:05:09.600
[Amit Varma]: and now podcasting and all of that.

00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:14.080
[Amit Varma]: And your career is also seems, you know, even more interesting than mine, because you actually

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:16.640
[Amit Varma]: share the poker player part of it.

00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:20.440
[Amit Varma]: And plus, you you know, you were an MBA and I am Ahmedabad.

00:05:20.440 --> 00:05:24.300
[Amit Varma]: You were a banker in New York, where you also studied the Lee Strasberg school.

00:05:24.300 --> 00:05:26.080
[Amit Varma]: And now you've come back here.

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:30.640
[Amit Varma]: And you're not just acting, you're also you know, you wrote a lovely short film recently

00:05:30.640 --> 00:05:32.320
[Amit Varma]: banana bread.

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:36.800
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about your journey and you know, how you took all these twists

00:05:36.800 --> 00:05:37.800
[Amit Varma]: and turns.

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:41.600
[Guest 2]: Well, on paper, that sounds wonderful in the way you if you introduce it like that, then

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:44.520
[Guest 2]: suddenly I start feeling good about myself.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:47.880
[Guest 2]: But yeah, I remember your I first heard of you and you were a cricket writer.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:51.440
[Guest 2]: So I'd heard of the Amit Verma and I think that's what I said to you when we first met

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:54.480
[Guest 2]: is, oh, you're that Amit Verma because you know, I read a lot of your stuff.

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:55.480
[Guest 2]: I'm a huge cricket fan.

00:05:55.480 --> 00:05:57.120
[Guest 2]: So I read your stuff.

00:05:57.120 --> 00:06:00.560
[Guest 2]: And then of course, we met very often on the poker tables.

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:06.280
[Guest 2]: As far as my journey was concerned, I I started off my life doing something completely different.

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:11.320
[Guest 2]: As you've mentioned, I did a classical MBA and you know, according to finance and I was

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:14.220
[Guest 2]: lucky enough to get a job on Wall Street and Lehman Brothers.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:17.160
[Guest 2]: So I was for the most part, I was a research analyst.

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:24.560
[Guest 2]: I was analyzing the debt of these big behemoths, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, primarily, I was

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:30.400
[Guest 2]: the lead analyst on their debt and other US agencies is pointless for some of your listeners.

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:33.040
[Guest 2]: But I was analyzing their debt for the most part of what I did.

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:37.480
[Guest 2]: I was there on Lehman Brothers for six years in New York.

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:40.600
[Guest 2]: And yeah, acting was always something that I was interested in.

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:46.400
[Guest 2]: But I think growing up at the time I did grow up, it wasn't an easy decision or it wasn't

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:50.880
[Guest 2]: something you did if you, you know, if especially if you're good in studies, you know that unfortunately,

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:51.880
[Guest 2]: that's how we grew up.

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:55.720
[Guest 2]: You know, it was people became actors if they weren't good in studies or at least that was

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:58.600
[Guest 2]: what we were told by parents and everybody else.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:06:59.800
[Guest 2]: So I was always interested.

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:02.920
[Guest 2]: I always was on stage in school, in college, etc.

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:08.680
[Guest 2]: And even while in New York, we started a theater group called Alter Ego, which was for people

00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:14.000
[Guest 2]: who were working professionals, we'd rehearse only on weekends and weeknights.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:18.680
[Guest 2]: And then I did classes at least, but to me, it was always a sort of very serious hobby.

00:07:18.680 --> 00:07:21.920
[Guest 2]: You know, I never thought of it as something more than that.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:25.400
[Guest 2]: But obviously, somewhere down the line, working at Lehman Brothers, Wall Street wasn't for

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:26.400
[Guest 2]: me.

00:07:26.400 --> 00:07:28.520
[Guest 2]: One part was I really wanted to come back to India.

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:32.120
[Guest 2]: And the other was I just, you know, I just, you know, while the finance part interested

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:36.000
[Guest 2]: me academically while studying it, and even initially in the first few years, and the

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.840
[Guest 2]: good part about Wall Street is that they don't illusions from day one, you know, you pretty

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:44.600
[Guest 2]: much enter and they tell you how much of a dog-eat-dog world it is.

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:46.640
[Guest 2]: And everybody's just out to make money.

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:50.000
[Guest 2]: And you know, whether you're screwing the customer, it doesn't really matter.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.200
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, there's absolutely no, you know, nobody gets disillusioned along the

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:56.200
[Guest 2]: way.

00:07:56.200 --> 00:08:01.560
[Guest 2]: So you realize very much, you know, in advance that either this is for me or not for me.

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:03.480
[Guest 2]: But it's also very hard to quit a job like that.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:07.040
[Guest 2]: So it took me a while before I could muster up the courage to quit.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:09.120
[Guest 2]: Also, I didn't know what else I would do.

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:12.520
[Guest 2]: So I wanted to move back to India, but I didn't know what I would do.

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:17.000
[Guest 2]: In fact, when I would come back to India on holidays, I would meet friends of mine, you

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.920
[Guest 2]: know, ex-classmates and ask them in finance, you know, and say, you know, what are you

00:08:20.920 --> 00:08:21.920
[Guest 2]: guys doing?

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:23.720
[Guest 2]: And you know, what could I move back and do?

00:08:23.720 --> 00:08:27.520
[Guest 2]: And all of them said that we want to move to where you are working, you know, they want

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:29.680
[Guest 2]: to quit their jobs and move to New York.

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:35.000
[Guest 2]: So I found that it would be very hard to perhaps move to a place where everyone's aspiring

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.960
[Guest 2]: to go to where I've come from.

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:38.200
[Guest 2]: And I didn't know what I'd want to do.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:43.000
[Guest 2]: So eventually, I think after, you know, a long time of thinking about it, and dragging

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.320
[Guest 2]: my feet on it for a while, it took me six years.

00:08:45.320 --> 00:08:49.200
[Guest 2]: And then I finally quit and I moved back to India without anything, which I know shocked

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:53.720
[Guest 2]: everybody in my family, because they couldn't understand how I could do something like that.

00:08:53.720 --> 00:08:58.240
[Guest 2]: And you know, here I was the poster child for all, you know, relatives, I mean, NRI

00:08:58.240 --> 00:09:01.760
[Guest 2]: banker in New York, and then I was unemployed in Bombay.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:06.440
[Guest 2]: And I think I wouldn't say that I chose to become an actor then, in fact, I did not.

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:08.360
[Guest 2]: That would have been too much of a leap for me.

00:09:08.360 --> 00:09:13.680
[Guest 2]: I told myself I'm taking a sabbatical a couple of years, because I didn't know what I wanted

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:14.680
[Guest 2]: to do.

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:18.320
[Guest 2]: So the two things I was interested in were writing and acting, and I wanted to explore

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:19.320
[Guest 2]: them.

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:22.960
[Guest 2]: So I thought I'd do that for a couple of years, a year or two years and, and then see where

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:23.960
[Guest 2]: you know, life takes me.

00:09:23.960 --> 00:09:28.880
[Guest 2]: I mean, I somewhere I think I always imagined I might have, you know, started as some something

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:31.840
[Guest 2]: on my own, or got another job later.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:36.080
[Guest 2]: But you know, because I was doing theatre for a while or writing, I might, you know,

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:37.520
[Guest 2]: get a leg into that world.

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:41.760
[Guest 2]: And maybe hopefully do you know, like we did in New York, you know, do evening rehearsals

00:09:41.760 --> 00:09:44.080
[Guest 2]: and acting plays once in a while.

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:49.720
[Guest 2]: But once I started doing it, and the writing didn't go very far, I have a lot of unfinished,

00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:53.160
[Guest 2]: some finished and a lot of unfinished stories on my laptop.

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:55.200
[Guest 2]: So which I hope to get back to someday.

00:09:55.200 --> 00:10:00.240
[Guest 2]: So yes, in that sense, you know, banana bread was wonderful for me to, you know, I wrote

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:03.680
[Guest 2]: it together, it really felt wonderful to be able to fulfil some part of that.

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:06.240
[Guest 2]: But the writing didn't really go very far.

00:10:06.240 --> 00:10:10.840
[Guest 2]: The acting did in the sense I started doing theatre in Bombay, and it's easier because

00:10:10.840 --> 00:10:14.480
[Guest 2]: you know, writing is a very solitary, as you know, it's a very solitary occupation.

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:18.760
[Guest 2]: It's not just the skill, it's also the temperament to keep doing things and, and manage to finish

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:19.760
[Guest 2]: work.

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:23.920
[Guest 2]: Whereas with theatre, once you join a play, which is what I did, you know, the rehearsal

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:27.240
[Guest 2]: schedule is set, you know, there's a show date, you have to do it.

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:29.200
[Guest 2]: And so I started doing that.

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:32.720
[Guest 2]: And I enjoyed it enough that I didn't quit, you know, it was a so called sabbatical for

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:35.360
[Guest 2]: maybe a year initially, then it became two years.

00:10:35.360 --> 00:10:37.160
[Guest 2]: And then I was just stretching it on.

00:10:37.160 --> 00:10:41.320
[Guest 2]: Because I didn't, I didn't have the guts, I think, to admit to myself that I wanted

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:43.040
[Guest 2]: to do this full time.

00:10:43.040 --> 00:10:47.240
[Guest 2]: So it just kept, but I wasn't quitting either, you know, I was continuing to do this.

00:10:47.240 --> 00:10:50.960
[Guest 2]: And I did this for a while, I think I just continued, I think, if I have any regrets,

00:10:50.960 --> 00:10:54.960
[Guest 2]: though, that, you know, a couple of years after that, also, when I was kind of telling

00:10:54.960 --> 00:11:00.320
[Guest 2]: myself, I'm kind of doing this semi seriously, but not, you know, as a full time career,

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:04.800
[Guest 2]: I didn't admit that to myself, until I was doing it long enough that one fine day I realised,

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:08.280
[Guest 2]: you know, I have become a full time actor, I mean, I'm doing this.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:09.680
[Guest 2]: So it did take me a little while.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:14.320
[Guest 2]: But yeah, that's, that's kind of the journey with, you know, as to how I became an actor.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:17.760
[Amit Varma]: And the little part of your eclectic background that I forgot to mention is that you were

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:22.760
[Amit Varma]: a Chadha brought up in Chennai, and you can make great dosas, which is also fascinating.

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:26.720
[Amit Varma]: And you were talking about sort of, you know, writing being the solitary act and the rest

00:11:26.720 --> 00:11:30.440
[Amit Varma]: of it working out, because you know, you're working with other people, and there are constantly

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:31.440
[Amit Varma]: things happening.

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:35.760
[Amit Varma]: And it seemed to me that, you know, that trade off is interesting, because when I was a kid,

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:40.320
[Amit Varma]: I was torn between do I want to be a writer or do I one day want to direct films, because

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:42.800
[Amit Varma]: I was into a lot of world cinema and all of that.

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:47.040
[Amit Varma]: And then I thought, no, if I'm writing something, I am completely in control of what I'm writing.

00:11:47.040 --> 00:11:51.720
[Amit Varma]: If I'm into, you know, the industry, I have to then coordinate with a bunch of people

00:11:51.720 --> 00:11:55.320
[Amit Varma]: sell my ideas to others, there are so many things out of my control.

00:11:55.320 --> 00:11:58.880
[Amit Varma]: So which is why I kind of came to writing, but it's interesting that, you know, your

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:03.400
[Amit Varma]: journey seems so almost so serendipitous, like, you know, John Lennon says, life is

00:12:03.400 --> 00:12:05.520
[Amit Varma]: what happens to you when you're busy making other plans.

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:10.400
[Amit Varma]: And it's that kind of a feeling, Rasika, it's kind of, you know, from, you know, the interviews

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:14.360
[Amit Varma]: that I watched of yours on YouTube, and so on, it, it feels a bit like that, as well,

00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:19.160
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that, you know, you were almost on the way to becoming like a policy wonk,

00:12:19.160 --> 00:12:22.400
[Amit Varma]: the kind of person who would be on my show anyway.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:27.520
[Amit Varma]: But then you move from kind of research to acting, tell me a bit about that journey,

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:32.160
[Amit Varma]: like was acting something you were always interested in and considered or did it just,

00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:36.720
[Amit Varma]: you know, grow from an interest to something more than that?

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:42.840
[Guest 1]: Not so consciously, actually, even if it was, I wasn't really thinking of it that consciously.

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:48.240
[Guest 1]: And I didn't really think that it could be a career primarily because there was no precedence

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:51.920
[Guest 1]: of that in the environment that I grew up in.

00:12:51.920 --> 00:12:59.720
[Guest 1]: So I grew up in Jamshedpur and my father runs a business and my mother runs a boutique.

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:06.200
[Guest 1]: And I didn't really think that acting could be a career that was not a part of my worldview.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:10.640
[Guest 1]: But I was always one of those people in school who would jump on stage at the drop of a hat,

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:14.760
[Guest 1]: you know, and was very happy to be on stage, but that's about it.

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:22.120
[Guest 1]: Then I went to Delhi University and I studied at LSR and I was studying Maths Honours much

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:23.120
[Guest 1]: like Mukul.

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:29.280
[Guest 1]: Mukul was also studying Maths Honours many years before me.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:37.080
[Guest 1]: So I think LSR is the first place where I would say I started acting seriously because

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:42.040
[Guest 1]: I was introduced suddenly to a new world where I realized that there's a lot to learn and

00:13:42.040 --> 00:13:44.240
[Guest 1]: there's so much talent.

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:50.280
[Guest 1]: And most of the people I interacted with at LSR, they'd all done theatre for a while and

00:13:50.280 --> 00:13:55.840
[Guest 1]: trained under professionals and they just knew so much more than my little Jamshedpur

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:58.440
[Guest 1]: life had exposed me to.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:02.840
[Guest 1]: So I was quite taken in by all of that.

00:14:02.840 --> 00:14:08.920
[Guest 1]: So Maths was one of the toughest subjects in Delhi University and I was so honestly

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:12.320
[Guest 1]: very bored and I still think that was one of the worst decisions in my life.

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest 1]: I would have loved to study History or Political Science or even Economics at DU, but I was

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:25.560
[Guest 1]: quite bored with Maths Honours and so I started doing a lot of theatre on the side and I started

00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:28.160
[Guest 1]: watching a lot of theatre in Delhi also.

00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:33.280
[Guest 1]: So I wouldn't go back home for holidays, would take buses to the Habitat Centre and or the

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:40.560
[Guest 1]: Sriram Centre and watch a lot of plays and also try and do as much theatre as I could,

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:45.480
[Guest 1]: as much as a rigorous course as Maths Honours allowed me to.

00:14:45.480 --> 00:14:51.960
[Guest 1]: So I think my first real acting experience was with a lovely theatre person called Anamika

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:56.200
[Guest 1]: Haksal, who's recently made a film as well.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:15:00.680
[Guest 1]: And the first play I did was a play called Riders to the Sea and we did the translated

00:15:00.680 --> 00:15:03.040
[Guest 1]: version in Hindi.

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:09.000
[Guest 1]: And so that was my first acting experience and I was quite taken in by all of that and

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:13.640
[Guest 1]: very interested in what I was doing at LSR as part of the Dramatic Society.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:17.720
[Guest 1]: But again, there was so much talent around me that I didn't have the confidence to apply

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:22.880
[Guest 1]: to NSD, which was the only other thing that I knew of around in which you train as an

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:23.880
[Guest 1]: actor.

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:27.200
[Guest 1]: So I didn't really take that seriously, I didn't know what to do after college, but

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:34.720
[Guest 1]: enthu to tha bahut, you know, so whatever came my way, I was very happy to sort of take

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:35.720
[Guest 1]: that up enthusiastically.

00:15:35.720 --> 00:15:42.080
[Guest 1]: So when I was in my third year, the girl who was in the room in front of my room in the

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:52.000
[Guest 1]: hostel was filling a form for a Mass Communication course, one at Jamia, one at Xavier's and

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:53.480
[Guest 1]: one at Sophia's.

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:58.280
[Guest 1]: So I was sitting in her room and flipping through the brochure and I saw this brochure

00:15:58.280 --> 00:16:02.320
[Guest 1]: of the course of Social Communications Media at Sophia's.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:08.560
[Guest 1]: So I went through the list of subjects and one of them said, Film Studies and I said

00:16:08.560 --> 00:16:13.920
[Guest 1]: yeh bahut interesting hai and I had been part of some film clubs at LSR and had watched

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:22.560
[Guest 1]: a few films, but I never really got an opportunity to explore that further.

00:16:22.560 --> 00:16:30.000
[Guest 1]: In fact, my first recollection of being very mesmerized by a clip of a film that I saw

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:39.040
[Guest 1]: was at, funnily enough, at a conference on conflict and peace, which was initiated by

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:45.720
[Guest 1]: an organization that the then principal of LSR, Dr. Meenakshi Gopinath used to run.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:52.760
[Guest 1]: And somebody showed a clip of Pather Panchali and I was very taken in by that clip and it

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:57.800
[Guest 1]: stayed with me for a while, but I didn't really get an opportunity to sort of watch a lot

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:00.280
[Guest 1]: of films while I was at hostel.

00:17:00.280 --> 00:17:05.160
[Guest 1]: And things were not available on DLD and online as they are today.

00:17:05.160 --> 00:17:08.760
[Guest 1]: So when I saw Film Studies in that brochure, I said, chalo yeh toh interesting hai, let

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:09.760
[Guest 1]: me apply for it.

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:13.600
[Guest 1]: And I also applied for it because it was one of the only courses which had an entrance

00:17:13.600 --> 00:17:17.520
[Guest 1]: exam after my exams at Maths Honours would have finished.

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:20.720
[Guest 1]: So it was kind of by chance.

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:26.560
[Guest 1]: So I applied to Social Communications Media and the girl whose brochure I was going through,

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:33.120
[Guest 1]: I don't think she got through, but I did.

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:36.320
[Guest 1]: And I didn't think that I really wanted to study that course.

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:38.440
[Guest 1]: I didn't know what I wanted to do.

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:43.320
[Guest 1]: And my parents said, oh, I think you should go abroad to study something.

00:17:43.320 --> 00:17:44.760
[Guest 1]: You know, it was that kind of a thing.

00:17:44.760 --> 00:17:48.760
[Guest 1]: And they said, chalo 16th year of education ho jayega, kar lo yeh course.

00:17:48.760 --> 00:17:49.760
[Guest 1]: Aise theek hai.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:56.520
[Guest 1]: So I went to Sophia's and I think that one year at Sophia's was one of the best years

00:17:56.520 --> 00:17:57.520
[Guest 1]: of my life.

00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:03.920
[Guest 1]: I've never met a bunch of women or a bunch of people who I've studied with who are so

00:18:03.920 --> 00:18:05.400
[Guest 1]: like each other.

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:11.320
[Guest 1]: We were all from similar backgrounds, similar colleges.

00:18:11.320 --> 00:18:16.600
[Guest 1]: And we were probably all the kind of people in college who are very enthusiastic about

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:17.600
[Guest 1]: anything, you know.

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:23.000
[Guest 1]: So it was very interesting to be a part of that course and journalism was also one of

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
[Guest 1]: the papers.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:29.280
[Guest 1]: And Jerry Pinto was a teacher, P. Sainath was a teacher, Paromita took a few classes

00:18:29.280 --> 00:18:30.280
[Guest 1]: on filmmaking.

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:33.960
[Guest 1]: So very interesting bunch of people.

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:40.800
[Guest 1]: And I think I was very moved by every class that I attended at Sophia's.

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:45.840
[Guest 1]: After Sophia's, after I finished that one year course, again, I didn't know what to

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:49.400
[Guest 1]: do because the course is very interesting, it teaches you a lot.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:53.520
[Guest 1]: And most importantly, it gives you a very interesting worldview, but you're not really

00:18:53.520 --> 00:18:57.240
[Guest 1]: specialized in anything to take that further.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:18:58.520
[Guest 1]: So I didn't know what to do.

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:05.320
[Guest 1]: So I wrote emails to a couple of people and said, you know, I think I want to be a research

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:06.320
[Guest 1]: assistant.

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:09.560
[Guest 1]: I just want to help somebody gather some information.

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:12.760
[Guest 1]: That's how vague my intent was.

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:18.080
[Guest 1]: And I got an email from somebody which said that Abhijeet Banerjee and Rohini Pandey are

00:19:18.080 --> 00:19:22.360
[Guest 1]: starting a research project which is based in Lucknow and they're looking for somebody

00:19:22.360 --> 00:19:26.400
[Guest 1]: to get secondary research data material for them.

00:19:26.400 --> 00:19:28.920
[Guest 1]: I didn't know what that even meant, honestly.

00:19:28.920 --> 00:19:32.440
[Guest 1]: I had no academic background in the social sciences.

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:38.400
[Guest 1]: I had not studied even statistics, you know, I was a math student.

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:43.520
[Guest 1]: So I said, this sounds like fun, I'll move to Lucknow, so I packed my bags and a week

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:51.880
[Guest 1]: later I was in Lucknow and trying to make inroads into PWD offices, the Vidhan Sabha

00:19:51.880 --> 00:19:54.560
[Guest 1]: to get information for Abhijeet and Rohini's project.

00:19:54.560 --> 00:20:00.080
[Guest 1]: I didn't understand how that information was really going to be used or anything like that.

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:06.280
[Guest 1]: But I was pretty good at it because enthusiasm, of course, and also I think people are less

00:20:06.280 --> 00:20:09.640
[Guest 1]: suspicious of a young woman trying.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:15.960
[Guest 1]: So I would say, sir, we have a college project, so please let me come to the library.

00:20:15.960 --> 00:20:20.840
[Guest 1]: So I would get access to a lot of things which otherwise might be, you know, wrapped in a

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:22.280
[Guest 1]: lot of bureaucracy.

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:26.680
[Guest 1]: So I collected that material for them and they were quite happy with what I had done.

00:20:26.680 --> 00:20:30.600
[Guest 1]: So I was even more encouraged to stick around.

00:20:30.600 --> 00:20:36.560
[Guest 1]: So I worked on the project for about five months and then I think just living in Lucknow

00:20:36.560 --> 00:20:41.680
[Guest 1]: alone and not having a bunch of friends and not being able to access public space like

00:20:41.680 --> 00:20:47.720
[Guest 1]: I had become used to accessing in Bombay, I decided that I wanted to move back.

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:53.480
[Guest 1]: So I started looking for similar jobs in Bombay and somebody wrote me an email saying that

00:20:53.480 --> 00:21:00.760
[Guest 1]: Pukar, which was an organization started by Arjuna Padure, Partners for Urban Knowledge

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:05.800
[Guest 1]: Action and Research, they were doing a project on gender and public space, which was being

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:11.840
[Guest 1]: done by Shilpa Phatke, Sameera Khan and Shilpa Ranade.

00:21:11.840 --> 00:21:16.800
[Guest 1]: So I wrote them an email and I got that job as a research assistant and I came back to

00:21:16.800 --> 00:21:19.320
[Guest 1]: Bombay to work on that.

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:28.120
[Guest 1]: That was slightly more interesting, but because it was not qualitative, it was an ethnographic

00:21:28.120 --> 00:21:29.120
[Guest 1]: kind of study.

00:21:29.120 --> 00:21:35.480
[Guest 1]: So it required me to actually study the behavior of women in public spaces.

00:21:35.480 --> 00:21:42.320
[Guest 1]: So I would go to stations regularly and watch food stalls and who stood at a food stall

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:45.840
[Guest 1]: to eat their food, who just carried their food and left.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:52.560
[Guest 1]: And mostly, most women, it was really startling to see that women would not stand and eat

00:21:52.560 --> 00:21:54.280
[Guest 1]: at a public stall.

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:59.200
[Guest 1]: So I worked on that project for a long time and my friends would make fun of me that,

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:02.760
[Guest 1]: so how many toilets are there for women in Andheri Station?

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:06.000
[Guest 1]: And there was a time when I knew exactly what the figures were.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:09.280
[Guest 1]: I would say, Andheri East Station mein itna hai, Andheri West mein itna hai because I

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:11.280
[Guest 1]: had done all of that.

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:14.040
[Guest 1]: So and how the toilets function and all of that.

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:19.040
[Guest 1]: So it was very interesting to do that, but I soon realized that while all of this is

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:24.240
[Guest 1]: interesting, unless I went and got a formal education in the social sciences, I would

00:22:24.240 --> 00:22:30.800
[Guest 1]: not really be able to understand this more than what I understand of it today.

00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:33.800
[Guest 1]: And I really didn't feel like I had the energy for that.

00:22:33.800 --> 00:22:37.960
[Guest 1]: And I'd heard a lot of academic conversations around me.

00:22:37.960 --> 00:22:43.440
[Guest 1]: And while they were very interesting, I also felt like it was not my cup of tea.

00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:47.680
[Guest 1]: I wanted something which was more tangible, maybe.

00:22:47.680 --> 00:22:53.720
[Guest 1]: So that's when I was flipping through the newspaper one day and I found that FDII was

00:22:53.720 --> 00:22:55.440
[Guest 1]: restarting their acting course.

00:22:55.440 --> 00:22:56.440
[Guest 1]: This was in 2004.

00:22:56.440 --> 00:23:00.080
[Guest 1]: It had shut down in 76.

00:23:00.080 --> 00:23:03.160
[Guest 1]: I had studied film at Sophia's.

00:23:03.160 --> 00:23:09.720
[Guest 1]: So I was very mesmerized by the idea of a film school, and especially one like FDII,

00:23:09.720 --> 00:23:13.000
[Guest 1]: which had a history of dissent.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:16.280
[Guest 1]: So I said, this should be an interesting space.

00:23:16.280 --> 00:23:21.720
[Guest 1]: And I had a few friends from there, and they were totally in love with the idea of being

00:23:21.720 --> 00:23:22.720
[Guest 1]: in the institute.

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:28.560
[Guest 1]: So I'd heard about this wisdom tree where people sit together and talk about cinema,

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:31.560
[Guest 1]: and every evening you get to watch a film.

00:23:31.560 --> 00:23:37.680
[Guest 1]: And that the physical space, the place that FDII is located in, was once Prabhat Studios.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:41.040
[Guest 1]: And I was like, wow, I'm going to be a part of history.

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:45.600
[Guest 1]: You know, so that's when I applied for FDII.

00:23:45.600 --> 00:23:53.040
[Guest 1]: I didn't think I would make it because there was a very rigorous three-round entrance exam.

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:57.720
[Guest 1]: And the last round was a four-day workshop in the institute.

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:01.520
[Guest 1]: And when I met the people who were there at the workshop, they'd all come with a lot of

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:05.560
[Guest 1]: experience and a lot of varied experiences.

00:24:05.560 --> 00:24:11.600
[Guest 1]: Somebody had worked with Naya Theatre for years, somebody was in the Sriram Repertory.

00:24:11.600 --> 00:24:17.400
[Guest 1]: And I had had no acting experience since LSR, so I hadn't done a performance for the last

00:24:17.400 --> 00:24:20.920
[Guest 1]: three years before I went to that four-day workshop.

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:25.760
[Guest 1]: And I was very shy, and it was very difficult for me to really do anything at that workshop.

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:29.280
[Guest 1]: And I didn't think I would make it, but I did.

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:36.560
[Guest 1]: There were 20 people who were selected, and for some reason, I was a part of that list.

00:24:36.560 --> 00:24:42.280
[Guest 1]: Once I joined the institute, I think that's when it possibly became different for Mukul

00:24:42.280 --> 00:24:43.280
[Guest 1]: and me.

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:47.760
[Guest 1]: About six months into the institute, I knew that this is what I wanted to do for a really,

00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:48.760
[Guest 1]: really long time.

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:53.080
[Guest 1]: And I wasn't willing to accept even for a single day that it wouldn't work out, you

00:24:53.080 --> 00:24:54.080
[Guest 1]: know.

00:24:54.080 --> 00:25:00.920
[Guest 1]: So I came to Bombay with that momentum, and really with a desire to get as much work as

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:01.920
[Guest 2]: I could.

00:25:01.920 --> 00:25:05.560
[Guest 2]: No, I just want to say, I think, you know, Rasika just said that it was different for

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:08.680
[Guest 2]: her and me in that sense, that she was very clear she wanted to be an actor.

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:15.840
[Guest 2]: And I have to say that I think, when I met Rasika, I think her sort of focus at wanting

00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:19.280
[Guest 2]: to be an actor had a big influence on me.

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:24.120
[Guest 2]: Because I was, until then, you know, sort of dabbling in multiple things, like we talked

00:25:24.120 --> 00:25:25.120
[Guest 2]: about.

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:26.120
[Guest 2]: And you said, you know, you did something similar.

00:25:26.120 --> 00:25:28.600
[Guest 2]: I think it also comes from having, you know, varied interests.

00:25:28.600 --> 00:25:29.600
[Guest 2]: You know, I played poker for a while.

00:25:29.600 --> 00:25:33.240
[Guest 2]: You know, not that I ever thought that that's a career, but you know, I took it very seriously

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:34.280
[Guest 2]: for some time.

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:38.600
[Guest 2]: I even started with an ex-colleague from Lehman while I was in Bombay.

00:25:38.600 --> 00:25:43.240
[Guest 2]: We started a firm that was looking for investing opportunities in the equity markets in India.

00:25:43.240 --> 00:25:45.440
[Guest 2]: And we started a firm, and we were doing that work.

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:48.680
[Guest 2]: So I kind of dabbled in multiple things.

00:25:48.680 --> 00:25:51.440
[Guest 2]: And I sort of liked that as well.

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:56.280
[Guest 2]: And I have to say that, you know, seeing Rasika's single-minded focus was also an influence

00:25:56.280 --> 00:25:59.480
[Guest 2]: because I also realized that, you know, if you want to get ahead in any one career, you

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:02.640
[Guest 2]: kind of have to push yourself somewhere.

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:08.080
[Guest 2]: And I think somewhere the lack of that drive or focus was affecting me and probably also

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:12.280
[Guest 2]: helped me say, okay, you know, I really need to narrow down a few things here and focus

00:26:12.280 --> 00:26:13.280
[Amit Varma]: in one direction.

00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:14.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:19.760
[Amit Varma]: And Rasika, you were talking about your sort of time at LSR where, you know, you felt that

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:23.120
[Amit Varma]: all these people around me are so accomplished, they've been doing theater for so long and

00:26:23.120 --> 00:26:24.120
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah.

00:26:24.120 --> 00:26:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And the thought that kind of struck me in my, you know, follow up question is from there.

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:32.600
[Amit Varma]: And one thought that struck me was that then it's sort of interesting that through that

00:26:32.600 --> 00:26:36.920
[Amit Varma]: journey that, you know, you are sort of where you are today, where you are, you know, fairly

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:41.760
[Amit Varma]: accomplished actress and so on and no doubt, you know, many of those other people haven't

00:26:41.760 --> 00:26:43.920
[Amit Varma]: quite managed to make the same journey.

00:26:43.920 --> 00:26:47.600
[Amit Varma]: And my question from there is, and no doubt a lot of this is, of course, you know, things

00:26:47.600 --> 00:26:51.360
[Amit Varma]: that happen to you and serendipity and luck and so on, there's no denying that.

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:56.160
[Amit Varma]: But equally, just thinking aloud, do you think the fact that you had these sort of unusual

00:26:56.160 --> 00:27:00.160
[Amit Varma]: backgrounds where you've done other things, where you've looked at life from a variety

00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:05.560
[Amit Varma]: of different angles, do you think that sort of made a difference in how you looked at

00:27:05.560 --> 00:27:06.800
[Amit Varma]: acting itself?

00:27:06.800 --> 00:27:10.880
[Amit Varma]: Because I would imagine that a lot of people who come into acting and want to be actors

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:12.720
[Amit Varma]: want to do nothing but that.

00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:16.960
[Amit Varma]: That's a whole kind of worldview when you sort of from the time you're a kid, you know,

00:27:16.960 --> 00:27:17.960
[Amit Varma]: that's what you want to do.

00:27:17.960 --> 00:27:19.920
[Amit Varma]: And you're in love with the industry and whatever.

00:27:19.920 --> 00:27:25.360
[Amit Varma]: But in your case, it seems in both your cases, it seems that number one, you're coming from

00:27:25.360 --> 00:27:31.000
[Amit Varma]: a variety of other places, you've both done maths and, you know, Mukul might even have

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:35.160
[Amit Varma]: foreseen the 2008 financial crisis coming if you were studying Fannie Mae and Fannie

00:27:35.160 --> 00:27:36.160
[Amit Varma]: Mac.

00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:37.920
[Amit Varma]: And we can't blame it on you.

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:40.720
[Amit Varma]: And he didn't foresee it, says Jessica.

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:44.240
[Guest 1]: A lot of friends give him credit for that.

00:27:44.240 --> 00:27:46.120
[Guest 1]: And I can tell you, he didn't.

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:47.120
[Guest 2]: No, I say I didn't.

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:49.760
[Guest 2]: I say very openly, of course, I didn't see that kind of crash.

00:27:49.760 --> 00:27:51.600
[Guest 2]: I mean, you knew there was something wrong happening.

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:52.600
[Guest 2]: And that I can talk about.

00:27:52.600 --> 00:27:53.840
[Guest 2]: There are fun stories there.

00:27:53.840 --> 00:27:55.920
[Guest 2]: But the kind of crash, no, no question.

00:27:55.920 --> 00:27:58.960
[Guest 2]: I wouldn't have believed that Lehman would have gone bankrupt.

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:04.300
[Amit Varma]: But do you think the sort of different perspectives and the different Nazarias sort of added something

00:28:04.300 --> 00:28:08.360
[Amit Varma]: extra to what you were as actors and maybe added something to your journey?

00:28:08.360 --> 00:28:12.680
[Guest 2]: No, I think it's hard for me to answer that question, first of all, you know, a perspective

00:28:12.680 --> 00:28:17.120
[Guest 2]: about your own life or to say what influenced you is very hard to answer.

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:20.840
[Guest 2]: But I think all actors draw from their own experiences, right?

00:28:20.840 --> 00:28:24.960
[Guest 2]: You have to draw from your own experiences of what you've done, people you've met, etc.

00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:30.760
[Guest 2]: But that's not to say that people who haven't necessarily had other careers haven't really

00:28:30.760 --> 00:28:33.400
[Guest 2]: had other experiences to draw from.

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:37.480
[Guest 2]: So I'm not sure that I would, you know, agree entirely with that.

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:41.800
[Guest 2]: I think, you know, everybody draws from, I mean, some people come from, you know, troubled

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:44.920
[Guest 2]: childhoods, and maybe that helps them in some scene.

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:48.360
[Guest 2]: But it's not to say that, you know, somebody else, you know, may or may not be able to

00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:49.360
[Guest 2]: do that.

00:28:49.360 --> 00:28:51.240
[Guest 1]: So, yeah, all your experiences add up.

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:53.760
[Guest 2]: I don't think you necessarily need multiple careers.

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:55.760
[Guest 1]: That's my simple point of view.

00:28:55.760 --> 00:29:00.720
[Guest 1]: I sort of agree with that, because I, in fact, my interest in this career started because

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:07.520
[Guest 1]: I realized when I was at FDI, that no experience of mine will not be able to help me become

00:29:07.520 --> 00:29:09.240
[Guest 1]: a better actor, you know.

00:29:09.240 --> 00:29:14.000
[Guest 1]: So it's just about how you use that experience in your work.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:17.840
[Guest 1]: And that is, that's the craft of it, you know.

00:29:17.840 --> 00:29:27.320
[Guest 1]: So it's, it's not about going and looking out for newer experiences, or varied experiences.

00:29:27.320 --> 00:29:35.080
[Guest 1]: It's about how you, how a memory of any experience stays with you, and how you sort of mold that

00:29:35.080 --> 00:29:40.200
[Guest 1]: into a particular role and the choices you make along that way, along that path.

00:29:40.200 --> 00:29:43.080
[Guest 1]: So I think that's, that's the thing about it.

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:49.920
[Amit Varma]: I want to kind of explore a couple of dichotomies, now, sort of two very separate things sort

00:29:49.920 --> 00:29:50.920
[Amit Varma]: of coming together.

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:55.160
[Amit Varma]: And one is a dichotomy of sensibilities, like, you know, you've mentioned how watching a

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:58.720
[Amit Varma]: scene of Pathar Panchali made an impression on you, and then no doubt watching great world

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:01.560
[Amit Varma]: cinema at FDI, I would also have done the same.

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:04.600
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, Mukul was at Lee Strasberg, and all of that.

00:30:04.600 --> 00:30:08.280
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that, for example, when we compare Bollywood, or we compare Indian

00:30:08.280 --> 00:30:11.920
[Amit Varma]: mainstream cinema to world cinema, we just make a category error.

00:30:11.920 --> 00:30:18.640
[Amit Varma]: Because these are just two completely different art forms, even though they look similar.

00:30:18.640 --> 00:30:21.760
[Amit Varma]: Because your sensibilities are different, you're aiming for different things, there

00:30:21.760 --> 00:30:27.360
[Amit Varma]: is a different notion of realism, and, you know, how you should tell a story and all

00:30:27.360 --> 00:30:28.360
[Amit Varma]: of that.

00:30:28.360 --> 00:30:33.720
[Amit Varma]: And equally, I think some of this would also then reflect in the kind of acting that is

00:30:33.720 --> 00:30:34.720
[Amit Varma]: done.

00:30:34.720 --> 00:30:38.080
[Amit Varma]: Like many of our Bollywood big gudges, and of course, I won't take any names, but many

00:30:38.080 --> 00:30:42.400
[Amit Varma]: of our superstars of the past, if you look at them from the Western prism of what good

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:47.320
[Amit Varma]: acting is, it would just seem like they are ridiculously hamming it up, or they're overacting

00:30:47.320 --> 00:30:49.880
[Amit Varma]: or over performing, and it's very performative.

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:53.920
[Amit Varma]: It's emoting, as that unique Indian word goes, I don't think anyone outside India uses the

00:30:53.920 --> 00:30:55.360
[Amit Varma]: word emoting.

00:30:55.360 --> 00:31:01.840
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, what has sort of happened, coinciding with the, you know, the trajectory

00:31:01.840 --> 00:31:07.640
[Amit Varma]: of your careers is that there is that other sensibility also coming into play where we

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:12.560
[Amit Varma]: do in Indian cinema today, and Indian web series today and entertainment today, see

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:18.640
[Amit Varma]: a lot of acting, which even from a Western sensibility also would be considered outstanding,

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:21.160
[Amit Varma]: including some of the work that you guys have done.

00:31:21.160 --> 00:31:23.440
[Amit Varma]: So how was it navigating this?

00:31:23.440 --> 00:31:27.880
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, first of all, like, what is your personal philosophy and approach towards

00:31:27.880 --> 00:31:28.880
[Amit Varma]: acting?

00:31:28.880 --> 00:31:29.880
[Amit Varma]: How do you view acting?

00:31:29.880 --> 00:31:30.880
[Amit Varma]: And how do you view cinema?

00:31:30.880 --> 00:31:32.900
[Amit Varma]: And how do you define good cinema?

00:31:32.900 --> 00:31:37.440
[Amit Varma]: And then secondly, and I'm assuming that a certain part of that at least is influenced

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:39.760
[Amit Varma]: by these global sensibilities.

00:31:39.760 --> 00:31:43.600
[Amit Varma]: And then secondly, you are in Bombay trying to make a living where not everybody shares

00:31:43.600 --> 00:31:45.120
[Amit Varma]: that sensibility.

00:31:45.120 --> 00:31:49.240
[Amit Varma]: And when you, you know, go to a set to act, the expectations might be, you know, your

00:31:49.240 --> 00:31:55.240
[Amit Varma]: expectations and that of whoever you're working for, might be quite different, obviously,

00:31:55.240 --> 00:32:00.640
[Amit Varma]: in your respective filmographies, you've worked with people who share that more kind of modern

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:01.640
[Amit Varma]: sensibility.

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:04.960
[Amit Varma]: But how do you sort of think about this and navigate this?

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:08.880
[Amit Varma]: And does the awareness of this and you know, play a part?

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:17.400
[Guest 1]: I think that first, I don't, while I was influenced by a lot of world cinema, and I got an opportunity

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:22.960
[Guest 1]: to watch a lot of films at FDI that many people didn't, and I also got an opportunity to watch

00:32:22.960 --> 00:32:28.480
[Guest 1]: them on film, which I'm still very proud of, not on DVDs or digital.

00:32:28.480 --> 00:32:35.560
[Guest 1]: So while that was very exciting, I think that just by, by growing up in this country, Bollywood

00:32:35.560 --> 00:32:40.640
[Guest 1]: is a big influence in your life, you know, and you cannot deny it, even if you want to,

00:32:40.640 --> 00:32:47.000
[Guest 1]: you know, and I never wanted to, I embraced it as much as I was as mesmerized by Sridevi

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:52.560
[Guest 1]: as I was by Isabella Huppert, you know, so I did not judge either.

00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:57.120
[Guest 1]: I thought that both were different experiences.

00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:04.680
[Guest 1]: As far as your position in a film is concerned, as an actor, you're in a very strange sort

00:33:04.680 --> 00:33:05.680
[Guest 1]: of situation.

00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:09.240
[Guest 1]: And actually, a lot of people are in that situation or in a film set.

00:33:09.240 --> 00:33:17.160
[Guest 1]: So what's very exciting to me, and also very irritating to me very many times is that filmmaking

00:33:17.160 --> 00:33:23.480
[Guest 1]: is a very, very, it's a deeply personal process, but also very collaborative one.

00:33:23.480 --> 00:33:30.920
[Guest 1]: And as an actor, you don't have much agency, you know, you are pretty much at the mercy

00:33:30.920 --> 00:33:39.440
[Guest 1]: of a director, cinematographer, art director, your co actor, so many things which are making

00:33:39.440 --> 00:33:43.240
[Guest 1]: this moment or the scene happen for you.

00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:48.240
[Guest 1]: But fortunately or unfortunately, you're the face of it, you know, so you're sort of put

00:33:48.240 --> 00:33:53.760
[Guest 1]: in this spot where everybody's abilities have to sort of sink in together for you to be

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:55.440
[Guest 1]: able to do something.

00:33:55.440 --> 00:34:01.320
[Guest 1]: So it's actually a very strange situation to be in, I totally love being in that situation,

00:34:01.320 --> 00:34:06.400
[Guest 1]: because I love giving into somebody else's vision, because it takes responsibility off

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:07.720
[Guest 1]: my shoulders.

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:13.200
[Guest 1]: And at the same time, I am a fairly important part of making that vision happen.

00:34:13.200 --> 00:34:16.280
[Guest 1]: So I'm very happy to function like that.

00:34:16.280 --> 00:34:19.840
[Guest 1]: So I enjoy this position, but it can be very scary.

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:26.480
[Guest 1]: And sometimes this position is scary to me when I can totally live a moment, but I don't

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:29.160
[Guest 1]: know how it's going to be put together.

00:34:29.160 --> 00:34:35.000
[Guest 1]: So very often the politics of it is something that I get scared about, I feel like, will

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:39.040
[Guest 1]: the politics of this film be in sync with mine or not?

00:34:39.040 --> 00:34:46.280
[Guest 1]: So when I agree to do a project or not, it's my first concern is the politics of this project,

00:34:46.280 --> 00:34:51.320
[Guest 1]: thinking that, so the politics of my character might not be in sync with mine, which is great,

00:34:51.320 --> 00:34:57.800
[Guest 1]: in fact, because I'd love to play, for example, a right wing troll, you know, but and just

00:34:57.800 --> 00:35:00.600
[Guest 1]: to understand how that mind works.

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:05.320
[Guest 1]: And when you're working on a role, you have to, you can't be judging your own character,

00:35:05.320 --> 00:35:06.320
[Guest 1]: right?

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:13.040
[Guest 1]: So it would really require a lot of empathy and expansion of the heart to be able to understand

00:35:13.040 --> 00:35:17.320
[Guest 1]: somebody who is completely different from you.

00:35:17.320 --> 00:35:23.400
[Guest 1]: But it's important to me that the overall politics of what I've agreed to work on is

00:35:23.400 --> 00:35:27.800
[Guest 1]: something that I, is something that is aligned with mine.

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:31.320
[Guest 1]: So that's the situation that you are in as an actor.

00:35:31.320 --> 00:35:37.080
[Guest 1]: So that's one thing that I always look out for when, you know, collaborating with somebody.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:44.400
[Guest 1]: Also the sensibility of a project is something that I find you have indications for it, like

00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:48.840
[Guest 1]: somebody can narrate their story to you, you can see their previous work, and you can get

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:51.440
[Guest 1]: a sense of where they're coming from.

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:55.960
[Guest 1]: But really, it's a gamble, you know, how it turns out could be very, very different from

00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:56.960
[Guest 1]: what you had imagined.

00:35:56.960 --> 00:36:02.560
[Guest 1]: So as an actor, you're always in that position, you know, because you've lost, you don't have

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:09.440
[Guest 1]: any control after you've shot for the film, and largely a lot of work on the film is about

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:14.840
[Guest 1]: the editing is about the sound, and all of that, that's like a whole other thing that's

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:21.040
[Guest 1]: going to happen to your work, and you have no control to say in the matter, nobody shows

00:36:21.040 --> 00:36:22.520
[Guest 1]: the film to you till it's done.

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:28.000
[Guest 1]: I mean, you might see clips of it at the dub, and all of that, but you don't have control

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.480
[Guest 1]: over that side of things, you know.

00:36:30.480 --> 00:36:34.920
[Guest 1]: So I mean, yeah, those are the things that concern me while I'm working with somebody.

00:36:34.920 --> 00:36:41.480
[Guest 1]: And sensibility ka aap andaza laga sakte ho, but you can't really have surety on how this

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:44.240
[Guest 1]: project is going to turn out.

00:36:44.240 --> 00:36:50.360
[Guest 1]: So sometimes when I watch something that I've worked on, I feel that maybe artistically,

00:36:50.360 --> 00:36:54.480
[Guest 1]: it's not aligning with my sensibility, maybe the politics is fine, but, you know, it's

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:58.000
[Guest 1]: not really aligning with my sensibilities like that.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:02.880
[Guest 1]: It's not what I'd imagined it to be, but sometimes I'm pleasantly surprised also.

00:37:02.880 --> 00:37:09.560
[Guest 1]: I mean, when I saw Delhi Crime, I was very proud of what the director, the editor and

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:14.320
[Guest 1]: the cinematographer had done, because in spite of the fact that I'd read the script, and

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:20.000
[Guest 1]: I was, I was very assured that Richie's politics were totally in sync with mine.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.560
[Guest 1]: And so were his sensibilities were of a very high standard.

00:37:23.560 --> 00:37:31.680
[Guest 1]: But I was very moved by how they managed to humanize these rapists, you know, who through

00:37:31.680 --> 00:37:38.800
[Guest 1]: the whole series you're, and just that's just in the lensing, the editing, how you've lensed

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:44.040
[Guest 1]: the character, how long you've held the shot on them, and how you how you've lit them,

00:37:44.040 --> 00:37:45.040
[Guest 1]: you know.

00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:46.440
[Guest 1]: So it's just about those things.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:48.360
[Guest 1]: And I was so moved by that.

00:37:48.360 --> 00:37:54.080
[Guest 1]: So in this case, this particular case, what I watched, superseded my expectations of the

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:55.840
[Guest 1]: sensibility of the project.

00:37:55.840 --> 00:38:00.600
[Guest 1]: But there have been other cases in Mirzapur, for example, I felt like the intent was very

00:38:00.600 --> 00:38:02.160
[Guest 1]: good, and the writing was very good.

00:38:02.160 --> 00:38:08.080
[Guest 1]: But I felt like the way we visualize a woman who is, who's acknowledged as a sexual being

00:38:08.080 --> 00:38:10.960
[Guest 1]: is still, we still have a very long way to go.

00:38:10.960 --> 00:38:13.920
[Guest 1]: Because I think our visuals are still very sexual.

00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:14.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, fair enough.

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:19.160
[Amit Varma]: And that's, in fact, what I felt when I watched Mirzapur as well, Mukul.

00:38:19.160 --> 00:38:21.280
[Guest 2]: Yeah, this is a very difficult question you've asked.

00:38:21.280 --> 00:38:25.560
[Guest 2]: I mean, this whole notion, and I think it's something that I think about, you know, because

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:31.520
[Guest 2]: as an actor, you always wonder, what is good acting and what is not good acting, you know,

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:35.360
[Guest 2]: you read stuff that other people have said about it, because obviously, if you're doing

00:38:35.360 --> 00:38:37.280
[Guest 2]: something, you want to do it really well.

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:42.080
[Guest 2]: And again, you know, it's also very personal, because you're all always influenced by what

00:38:42.080 --> 00:38:43.080
[Unknown]: you have liked and not liked.

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:47.200
[Guest 2]: You know, I think at the end of the day, just like a director tells stories that he or she

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:53.040
[Guest 2]: has wants to tell, much like that, you want to do performances that you have enjoyed watching.

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:57.880
[Guest 2]: And that changes actually, over time, and it's very hard to quantify it and say, this

00:38:57.880 --> 00:38:58.880
[Guest 2]: is what is good.

00:38:58.880 --> 00:38:59.880
[Guest 2]: And this is what is bad.

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:04.480
[Guest 2]: I mean, growing up, I actually haven't had as much exposure to world cinema, I have watched

00:39:04.480 --> 00:39:08.200
[Guest 2]: a lot of Bollywood, some things I have loved, some things I've hated.

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:12.600
[Guest 2]: Even Western films I've seen, I've seen a lot more of the Hollywood blockbusters, than

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:16.560
[Guest 2]: you know, seeing a lot of foreign language films, which is more something that you know,

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:19.600
[Guest 2]: one is more exposed to now, but I had it.

00:39:19.600 --> 00:39:24.400
[Guest 2]: So a lot of things are influenced by, and even within the realm of what you watch, I

00:39:24.400 --> 00:39:27.960
[Guest 2]: feel, you know, there are things that you like more and things you like less, to me,

00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:31.120
[Guest 2]: a good performance is something that moves me in any way.

00:39:31.120 --> 00:39:34.840
[Guest 2]: And if I shut off, you know, and I say, no, this is fake, I don't buy this, or I don't

00:39:34.840 --> 00:39:38.320
[Guest 2]: believe it, then that's not really necessarily a good performance.

00:39:38.320 --> 00:39:39.320
[Guest 2]: But that changes.

00:39:39.320 --> 00:39:43.560
[Guest 2]: If I think back to some of the TV shows I watched in the 80s, you know, there's some

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:45.960
[Guest 2]: shows that we loved and thought they were great.

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:47.680
[Guest 2]: And you go back and watch them today.

00:39:47.680 --> 00:39:50.120
[Guest 2]: And a lot of them are unwatchable to me, right.

00:39:50.120 --> 00:39:54.600
[Guest 2]: And I think it's a function of having seen other things, you know, so I wouldn't put

00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:56.920
[Guest 2]: it's a classic problem of high art versus low art.

00:39:56.920 --> 00:39:57.920
[Guest 2]: What is high art?

00:39:57.920 --> 00:39:58.920
[Guest 2]: What is low art?

00:39:58.920 --> 00:40:01.680
[Guest 2]: How do you, how do you, you know, want to put a line on it, but I think the more you

00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:05.640
[Guest 2]: end up seeing, and it's great that there's so much competition, and people are influenced

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:10.880
[Guest 2]: by things that happen across the world, both ways, and the more you watch, you're drawn

00:40:10.880 --> 00:40:15.480
[Guest 2]: to things that then, you know, take it to a slightly higher standard, then something

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:18.480
[Guest 2]: that you liked earlier may not, you know, hold weight as much.

00:40:18.480 --> 00:40:20.080
[Guest 2]: And it's also a hard question to answer.

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:23.840
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's something what is over the top, what is not, you know, sometimes the genre

00:40:23.840 --> 00:40:27.600
[Guest 2]: of a film, I mean, was chapter over the top, because, you know, there's a lot of slapstick

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:28.600
[Guest 2]: stuff he's doing.

00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:31.320
[Guest 2]: But that within that genre, it works, you know, it works.

00:40:31.320 --> 00:40:32.320
[Guest 2]: And that makes you laugh.

00:40:32.320 --> 00:40:34.960
[Guest 2]: And that makes you feel okay, this is great.

00:40:34.960 --> 00:40:36.120
[Guest 2]: And you can watch it even today.

00:40:36.120 --> 00:40:41.200
[Guest 2]: So it's, it's very hard to sometimes, and it's a constant struggle, it's a good question,

00:40:41.200 --> 00:40:43.560
[Guest 2]: because it's something that you're never sure of.

00:40:43.560 --> 00:40:47.120
[Guest 2]: And when you take on a new project, you're trying to visualize it.

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:51.360
[Guest 2]: I mean, very often, it's, you know, you need to read the whole script to understand what

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:55.080
[Guest 2]: is the vision of what is the, you know, what is the genre is going to fit into what is

00:40:55.080 --> 00:40:59.360
[Guest 2]: the style this is going to be to understand, you know, what your role in it is, because

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:00.640
[Guest 2]: it has to fit within that.

00:41:00.640 --> 00:41:05.040
[Guest 2]: And like Jessica said, it's very, it's very difficult, because sometimes you don't know

00:41:05.040 --> 00:41:06.040
[Guest 2]: what the director wants.

00:41:06.040 --> 00:41:09.800
[Guest 2]: And the better ones are those who are able to, you know, communicate that to you, you

00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:14.400
[Guest 2]: know, where that you understand, you know, then what is the style and, and at some level,

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:20.160
[Guest 2]: you'd like to do work that you would like watching, you know, because then it's easier

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:22.080
[Guest 2]: to sort of, you know, fit into that.

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:24.680
[Guest 2]: And it could be across genres, you could do something very slapstick.

00:41:24.680 --> 00:41:25.680
[Guest 2]: And that's great.

00:41:25.680 --> 00:41:28.760
[Guest 2]: You could do something that's, you know, totally different.

00:41:28.760 --> 00:41:31.920
[Guest 2]: But as long as it's something you like doing, I'm not saying we always managed to do that,

00:41:31.920 --> 00:41:34.160
[Guest 2]: because while you're working, you end up doing a lot of other things.

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:37.800
[Guest 2]: And plus, you sometimes don't know how things are going to turn out.

00:41:37.800 --> 00:41:38.800
[Guest 2]: So that's separate.

00:41:38.800 --> 00:41:42.680
[Guest 2]: But yeah, I think it's a very difficult question to answer, because and it's constantly changing,

00:41:42.680 --> 00:41:46.840
[Guest 2]: you know, what is good acting, I see some performance somewhere.

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:50.320
[Guest 2]: And now, of course, we have so many shows from across the world that are just coming

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:52.800
[Guest 2]: into our living room without making any effort.

00:41:52.800 --> 00:41:56.720
[Guest 2]: And you know, you see something and you think, oh, this is interesting how someone has done

00:41:56.720 --> 00:41:57.720
[Guest 2]: something.

00:41:57.720 --> 00:42:03.240
[Guest 2]: And it's sometimes different from what, you know, you might have thought works earlier.

00:42:03.240 --> 00:42:10.720
[Guest 2]: So yeah, you know, what's good and bad, I think is a function of what you're drawn to.

00:42:10.720 --> 00:42:11.720
[Guest 2]: And that also keeps changing.

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:15.640
[Guest 2]: You know, I think what we may, you know, it's possible that what we think is good acting

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:19.320
[Guest 2]: today, you know, 30 years down the line, someone will say this was very mediocre.

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:20.320
[Guest 2]: It's possible.

00:42:20.320 --> 00:42:21.320
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:42:21.320 --> 00:42:22.320
[Amit Varma]: And that's very perceptive.

00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:26.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, to me, like you said, it's not just about a difference between high art and low

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:28.120
[Amit Varma]: art, but taste change over time.

00:42:28.120 --> 00:42:31.440
[Amit Varma]: Like, again, like you have tried watching the shows of the 1980s, when one gets him

00:42:31.440 --> 00:42:37.000
[Amit Varma]: on YouTube, like Yeh Jo Hai Zindagi and all of that.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:40.840
[Amit Varma]: And then you wonder about yourself, ki yaar, I used to like that.

00:42:40.840 --> 00:42:41.840
[Guest 2]: What was like?

00:42:41.840 --> 00:42:45.400
[Guest 2]: So Gudiyaan was always this soap, but Yeh Jo Hai Zindagi was the one, right?

00:42:45.400 --> 00:42:49.960
[Guest 2]: Because I remember laughing as a kid when I saw it and it was one of the better shows.

00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:50.960
[Guest 2]: And I watched it again.

00:42:50.960 --> 00:42:53.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, it is truly unwatchable for me right now.

00:42:53.920 --> 00:42:58.560
[Guest 2]: And I also feel that that's why when we diss a lot of TV soaps that are on right now in

00:42:58.560 --> 00:43:03.000
[Guest 2]: the last decade, it's wholly possible that they're being watched by a whole lot of people

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:07.080
[Guest 2]: who have got access to cable for the first time in the last 10 or 20 years.

00:43:07.080 --> 00:43:10.480
[Guest 2]: And once they start seeing better things, they will also no longer like it.

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:12.040
[Guest 2]: You know, it's just that.

00:43:12.040 --> 00:43:13.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:14.040
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:43:14.040 --> 00:43:17.040
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the thought struck me yesterday, I was kind of out on the road and I saw this

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:20.920
[Amit Varma]: very old vintage car, which looked so incredibly ugly and all of that.

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And then I realized that, wait a minute, when I was in my early 20s in Bombay, the Mitsubishi

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:28.680
[Amit Varma]: Lancer was the most beautiful freaking beast you could aspire to, right?

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:31.280
[Amit Varma]: And I saw one of those models a couple of days back on the street.

00:43:31.280 --> 00:43:35.840
[Amit Varma]: And I was like, my God, what an ugly thing, wait a minute, this is that, you know, and

00:43:35.840 --> 00:43:39.080
[Amit Varma]: then you wonder whether the kind of work that you do today will also change.

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:45.000
[Amit Varma]: I was sort of, you know, what you were saying, what, you know, Rasika was speaking about,

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:49.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, the approaches to acting, I was reminded of an old episode I did on the art

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:54.280
[Amit Varma]: of translation with Aruna Vasina, who's translated like 40 books from Bengali to English.

00:43:54.280 --> 00:43:58.320
[Amit Varma]: And he said something very interesting there, where he said that when we were speaking about

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:02.600
[Amit Varma]: languages and, you know, thinking in one language and writing in the other, and he made the

00:44:02.600 --> 00:44:07.500
[Amit Varma]: point that Indians, because we are so multilingual, are very good at code shifting.

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:12.420
[Amit Varma]: So we can automatically effortlessly shift from, you know, being natural in one language

00:44:12.420 --> 00:44:14.940
[Amit Varma]: to being natural in another language.

00:44:14.940 --> 00:44:20.560
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that in some way, these different schools of acting, as it were, are

00:44:20.560 --> 00:44:22.600
[Amit Varma]: also like different languages.

00:44:22.600 --> 00:44:26.880
[Amit Varma]: And it's not that you necessarily have to speak one or the other language, but you can

00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:31.080
[Amit Varma]: just adapt whichever one and even mix them up as required.

00:44:31.080 --> 00:44:32.920
[Amit Varma]: Does that kind of make any kind of sense?

00:44:32.920 --> 00:44:38.920
[Guest 2]: No, I mean, I'm also confused about the schools of acting in the sense, I haven't, you know,

00:44:38.920 --> 00:44:43.880
[Guest 2]: like, I haven't studied formal theatre, except at Least Strasbourg, where I studied and they

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:48.440
[Guest 2]: were very fixed on the method, you know, and that was their big thing that, you know, you

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:50.200
[Guest 2]: have to follow the method.

00:44:50.200 --> 00:44:56.560
[Guest 2]: But even within their, you know, and there was the opposition to the Stella Adler school,

00:44:56.560 --> 00:44:59.600
[Guest 2]: which was, you know, not a few blocks away, that that's a different style.

00:44:59.600 --> 00:45:04.960
[Guest 2]: And you have this, even within the method, I found my personal view was a lot of the

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:09.760
[Guest 2]: teachers were teaching us understood the method to be very different.

00:45:09.760 --> 00:45:14.440
[Guest 2]: And, you know, they would interpret it and they would have their own teaching styles.

00:45:14.440 --> 00:45:18.280
[Guest 2]: And but the one thing that I think stuck with me from what a lot of people have said, and

00:45:18.280 --> 00:45:22.960
[Guest 2]: teachers said, and otherwise also, you know, other theatre people you work with, is whatever

00:45:22.960 --> 00:45:26.520
[Guest 2]: works for you, something someone tells you works for you, and you hold on to it and something

00:45:26.520 --> 00:45:29.400
[Guest 2]: someone else says works for you.

00:45:29.400 --> 00:45:33.440
[Guest 2]: And yeah, I think I think that's, that's it for me, actually.

00:45:33.440 --> 00:45:40.360
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so you know, the thing is, what's exciting to me about my work is that there's no one

00:45:40.360 --> 00:45:41.720
[Guest 1]: way to do it.

00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:47.880
[Guest 1]: So in one, and there's no one basic set of rules that you have to follow either.

00:45:47.880 --> 00:45:49.920
[Guest 1]: So you change it up as you go along.

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:56.000
[Guest 1]: And so I wouldn't say that what I'm doing in one film could probably even qualify as

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:00.120
[Guest 1]: being called a language, you know, because there are the rules are not so set, you know,

00:46:00.120 --> 00:46:05.680
[Guest 1]: it's actually very experiential, and it's actually very, something that I improvised

00:46:05.680 --> 00:46:06.680
[Guest 1]: along the way.

00:46:06.680 --> 00:46:11.920
[Guest 1]: So yeah, your work on another project automatically does become different.

00:46:11.920 --> 00:46:18.480
[Guest 1]: But neither of them would be something that you would be able to use again somewhere else.

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:21.440
[Guest 1]: The other experience will be an entirely different experience.

00:46:21.440 --> 00:46:27.240
[Guest 1]: And what I'm interested in, earlier on in my career was I was like, anytime anybody

00:46:27.240 --> 00:46:31.280
[Guest 1]: would ask me, so what is your process, and I was like, my process is that I'm looking

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:32.920
[Guest 1]: for a process.

00:46:32.920 --> 00:46:40.160
[Guest 1]: And now I after having worked for around 12 years, I've realized that there can be no

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:42.560
[Guest 1]: one process for yourself.

00:46:42.560 --> 00:46:44.200
[Guest 1]: And that's the beauty of it.

00:46:44.200 --> 00:46:47.480
[Guest 1]: And I don't want there to be that one process.

00:46:47.480 --> 00:46:53.960
[Guest 1]: Yeah, there can be techniques that you rely on on a day where you're not completely there,

00:46:53.960 --> 00:46:59.880
[Guest 1]: where you're not having a very good day as an actor, where you're not able to be there

00:46:59.880 --> 00:47:01.560
[Guest 1]: for that part.

00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:02.560
[Guest 1]: And that moment.

00:47:02.560 --> 00:47:05.640
[Guest 1]: So there are techniques that you can fall back on.

00:47:05.640 --> 00:47:07.360
[Guest 1]: But there is no one way to do it.

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:12.240
[Guest 1]: And there shouldn't be is my assessment of it so far, I might change my mind next month.

00:47:12.240 --> 00:47:15.240
[Guest 1]: But this is how I feel about it today.

00:47:15.240 --> 00:47:16.400
[Amit Varma]: No, that's pretty insightful.

00:47:16.400 --> 00:47:21.520
[Amit Varma]: And if I try to sort of process it in my language, what you're saying is that look, we have a

00:47:21.520 --> 00:47:26.960
[Amit Varma]: set of tactics that we can use in any situation, but there's not necessarily one strategy,

00:47:26.960 --> 00:47:29.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, that can differ according to the task.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:33.400
[Amit Varma]: But then my follow up question, Rasika, would be that, even if there is no one process per

00:47:33.400 --> 00:47:39.080
[Amit Varma]: se, and it differs from project to project, is there then a set of values or an acting

00:47:39.080 --> 00:47:43.320
[Amit Varma]: ethic or an approach towards the characters that you play that is common, something common

00:47:43.320 --> 00:47:47.440
[Amit Varma]: there that you, you know, maybe the way that you approach the characters or approach your

00:47:47.440 --> 00:47:52.640
[Amit Varma]: role or just the ethic that you bring to the whole craft that is common and that, you know,

00:47:52.640 --> 00:47:53.640
[Guest 1]: that is common to everything.

00:47:53.640 --> 00:47:57.320
[Guest 1]: There are certain ethics that I have for myself.

00:47:57.320 --> 00:48:01.640
[Guest 1]: But I don't know if anybody else follows them.

00:48:01.640 --> 00:48:05.440
[Guest 1]: You know, I think if you I don't know if Mukul does, if you ask any other actor, I don't

00:48:05.440 --> 00:48:08.120
[Guest 1]: know, they might have their own set.

00:48:08.120 --> 00:48:15.280
[Guest 1]: But some of the things that I am very, very pakka about, and I don't let go of, one is

00:48:15.280 --> 00:48:20.240
[Guest 1]: that I will never, ever in my life, tell my co actor what to do.

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:21.240
[Guest 1]: Never.

00:48:21.240 --> 00:48:28.400
[Guest 1]: In fact, the beauty of a moment between two actors is the uncertainty of it and the many,

00:48:28.400 --> 00:48:30.600
[Guest 1]: the number of things that it can be.

00:48:30.600 --> 00:48:35.840
[Guest 1]: And the beautiful moment between two actors is when you can't put your finger on the emotion.

00:48:35.840 --> 00:48:41.960
[Guest 1]: Because you can only put your finger on the emotion when somebody is emoting.

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:46.800
[Guest 1]: And that, in my opinion, is not good acting, you know, good acting is when you when there's

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:52.920
[Guest 1]: confusion and there's a lot of so many other things and when there is when you can't put

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:58.080
[Guest 1]: your finger on one single emotion, you know, and there are so many things at play.

00:48:58.080 --> 00:49:04.680
[Guest 1]: And the moment you try and if you instruct your co actor on what to do, you're basically

00:49:04.680 --> 00:49:08.560
[Guest 1]: asking them to do something which is convenient to you.

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:15.720
[Guest 1]: And therefore, you're removing the possibility of magic, you are at the altar of efficiency,

00:49:15.720 --> 00:49:16.720
[Guest 1]: you know.

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:21.560
[Guest 1]: So because you're so insecure or nervous about trying to get a moment right and trying to

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:27.240
[Guest 1]: get it executed efficiently, you're losing out the possibility of magic and you know,

00:49:27.240 --> 00:49:33.480
[Guest 1]: few times that magic happens in the time between action and cut, it is so precious that you

00:49:33.480 --> 00:49:38.880
[Guest 1]: feel like my years of struggle and standing in Oshiwara outside studios and waiting for

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:43.120
[Guest 1]: auditions with my makeup melting has been worth it.

00:49:43.120 --> 00:49:48.640
[Guest 1]: So that's the beauty of that moment is so, so much that it makes me feel sad when people

00:49:48.640 --> 00:49:49.640
[Guest 1]: let go of it.

00:49:49.640 --> 00:49:54.520
[Guest 1]: When I see people letting go of it, I'm like, oh my god, you guys just like lost the opportunity

00:49:54.520 --> 00:50:00.560
[Guest 1]: to have a moment which was something that nobody would have thought out, or logically

00:50:00.560 --> 00:50:04.360
[Guest 1]: understood or rehearsed, you know.

00:50:04.360 --> 00:50:09.160
[Amit Varma]: So are there specific moments of magic that you remember from your career like this, which

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:12.240
[Amit Varma]: made you feel that I need more of this, for example, you've referred to the penultimate

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:16.160
[Amit Varma]: scene and Kissa with Irfan, which you, you know, you went and reshot and you said you

00:50:16.160 --> 00:50:18.240
[Amit Varma]: did eight takes, and they were also magical.

00:50:18.240 --> 00:50:21.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'm presuming that was kind of one of those.

00:50:21.840 --> 00:50:24.920
[Amit Varma]: But apart from that, you know, is this something that you started with?

00:50:24.920 --> 00:50:27.240
[Amit Varma]: Or is it something that you gradually discovered?

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:31.880
[Amit Varma]: Are there these moments of magic that you can point to and say that, you know, yes,

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:35.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, that moment happened, because I let it happen, because I didn't try to sort

00:50:35.160 --> 00:50:37.560
[Amit Varma]: of drive the process too hard?

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:41.880
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so Kissa was the first time it happened, as I remember it.

00:50:41.880 --> 00:50:44.000
[Guest 1]: And that's why it was so special.

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:50.160
[Guest 1]: And it was also, Kissa was, in one sense, the perfect film for an actor.

00:50:50.160 --> 00:50:56.040
[Guest 1]: The environment allowed you to thrive as a performer, you know, the director was somebody

00:50:56.040 --> 00:51:01.080
[Guest 1]: who was very sensitive to actors, protected us from every other thing happening on the

00:51:01.080 --> 00:51:02.080
[Guest 1]: set.

00:51:02.080 --> 00:51:06.120
[Guest 1]: The bunch of co-actors that I was working with, I mean, I had a co-actor like Irfan,

00:51:06.120 --> 00:51:12.200
[Guest 1]: like Dilotma, like Kiska, all people who are very accomplished and very much on the same

00:51:12.200 --> 00:51:16.040
[Guest 1]: page as I am about trying to make a scene work, you know.

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:21.960
[Guest 1]: So in that sense, Kissa was like a perfect experience and not the kind of experience

00:51:21.960 --> 00:51:24.080
[Guest 1]: that you find on other projects.

00:51:24.080 --> 00:51:30.800
[Guest 1]: But as I had more and more experience, I realized that I started enjoying fighting everything

00:51:30.800 --> 00:51:34.320
[Guest 1]: to make my moment work, you know, that became my thrill.

00:51:34.320 --> 00:51:38.560
[Guest 1]: Like, I was like, okay, all of you can yell and scream around me, but I will still find

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:43.080
[Guest 1]: my moment while I'm shooting, because that is what will remain.

00:51:43.080 --> 00:51:48.680
[Guest 1]: Nobody will remember that the light was not working, and that the sun was going to go

00:51:48.680 --> 00:51:53.200
[Guest 1]: down in two minutes, and you had only three minutes to get this shot done.

00:51:53.200 --> 00:51:57.280
[Guest 1]: And that your co-actor forgot their line, and the million other things that can go wrong

00:51:57.280 --> 00:52:00.760
[Guest 1]: on shoot, and that people were yelling and screaming at each other.

00:52:00.760 --> 00:52:04.960
[Guest 1]: So I've realized earlier, it used to really bother me, and I would really try and find

00:52:04.960 --> 00:52:10.480
[Guest 1]: my focus and concentration and go away and try and, you know, be like, guys, please don't

00:52:10.480 --> 00:52:13.560
[Guest 1]: interfere with my work and don't make this not work for me.

00:52:13.560 --> 00:52:17.760
[Guest 1]: But now I will just stand in the middle of all of it, and I will say, throw anything

00:52:17.760 --> 00:52:23.240
[Guest 1]: at me, and I will still try and make that shot work for myself.

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:30.000
[Guest 1]: The other thing that I do, besides one of the other rules that I have for myself, is

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:34.440
[Guest 1]: I will never play out a moment that is in the script before.

00:52:34.440 --> 00:52:41.560
[Guest 1]: I'm very wary of playing it away before the shot happens.

00:52:41.560 --> 00:52:44.120
[Guest 1]: So I'll read it a number of times.

00:52:44.120 --> 00:52:48.760
[Guest 1]: I might think different things about it every time I read it, every time I begin to read

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:51.840
[Guest 1]: the scene, I might approach it completely differently.

00:52:51.840 --> 00:52:55.800
[Guest 1]: But I will never decide that this is how I'm going to play this moment.

00:52:55.800 --> 00:53:02.480
[Guest 1]: But what I will do is I will equip my character with a world.

00:53:02.480 --> 00:53:05.960
[Guest 1]: I will make my character have a world that they exist in.

00:53:05.960 --> 00:53:11.880
[Guest 1]: So I will do things around that character, which need not necessarily even feature in

00:53:11.880 --> 00:53:12.880
[Guest 1]: the film.

00:53:12.880 --> 00:53:18.800
[Guest 1]: So that maybe no one will even know that I have done this work.

00:53:18.800 --> 00:53:25.600
[Guest 1]: But somewhere it will help, and it's also the most fun way to work on a character.

00:53:25.600 --> 00:53:30.200
[Guest 1]: Otherwise it's really boring, I don't know how else to do it.

00:53:30.200 --> 00:53:37.640
[Guest 1]: But basically, for example, for Kista, I read a lot of Punjabi poetry, I listened to a lot

00:53:37.640 --> 00:53:42.520
[Guest 1]: of Punjabi music, which ranged from Punjabi MC to Reshma.

00:53:42.520 --> 00:53:43.520
[Guest 1]: It was that varied.

00:53:43.520 --> 00:53:50.400
[Guest 1]: And I just thought that, because the character I was playing was somebody who was very free

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:51.400
[Guest 1]: and one with nature.

00:53:51.400 --> 00:53:57.320
[Guest 1]: You know, she's like this tribal Punjabi girl and so I felt like I needed to, maybe these

00:53:57.320 --> 00:53:58.320
[Guest 1]: things would help.

00:53:58.320 --> 00:54:02.080
[Guest 1]: I don't know if they did or didn't or how exactly they helped.

00:54:02.080 --> 00:54:09.040
[Guest 1]: But I felt like I was providing a world for Neeli, this character in Kista, to live in.

00:54:09.040 --> 00:54:13.000
[Guest 1]: Now, I was not deciding that I will do this in this scene.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:17.240
[Guest 1]: And that's something that I've tried to follow through the work that I've done.

00:54:17.240 --> 00:54:20.720
[Guest 1]: And that, I believe, leads to magical moments.

00:54:20.720 --> 00:54:27.600
[Guest 1]: And to give you another example of a magical moment was this moment in Delhi Crime, where

00:54:27.600 --> 00:54:33.240
[Guest 1]: I play Neeti Singh, who is a probationary officer, like they call it in the police.

00:54:33.240 --> 00:54:38.440
[Guest 1]: She's finished her training at the academy and is in the six months field training.

00:54:38.440 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest 1]: And she's found herself in this job that the DCP has given her.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:49.480
[Guest 1]: And there are protests at India Gate and she's asked to go manage those.

00:54:49.480 --> 00:54:54.400
[Guest 1]: And while I was shooting for that, and in the script at this time, she's been assigned

00:54:54.400 --> 00:54:57.840
[Guest 1]: to be at the hospital with the family and the girl.

00:54:57.840 --> 00:55:03.640
[Guest 1]: So she's been there and she's been up for three nights.

00:55:03.640 --> 00:55:09.000
[Guest 1]: And by right now, the character is in this space where all she wants is, she wants the

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:10.400
[Guest 1]: girl to be okay.

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:16.360
[Guest 1]: That's all she's focused, at least that's how I understood it at that point.

00:55:16.360 --> 00:55:22.800
[Guest 1]: And then we are shooting for this scene, and there are these protesters and there are these

00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:25.200
[Guest 1]: bunch of junior artists who've been organized.

00:55:25.200 --> 00:55:29.720
[Guest 1]: And there's complete chaos on set that day, because it's a very hard shot to pull off.

00:55:29.720 --> 00:55:33.800
[Guest 1]: And the moment you have many junior artists, things become very difficult production wise,

00:55:33.800 --> 00:55:36.760
[Guest 1]: and everybody's sort of wondering what to do.

00:55:36.760 --> 00:55:42.280
[Guest 1]: And there's a lot of chaos that you have to find moments within.

00:55:42.280 --> 00:55:47.320
[Guest 1]: So I remember she's holding the shield and she comes out.

00:55:47.320 --> 00:55:53.680
[Guest 1]: And on that day of shoot, I came out and I looked at these protesters and they were protesting

00:55:53.680 --> 00:55:54.680
[Guest 1]: against the police.

00:55:54.680 --> 00:55:55.680
[Guest 1]: And I felt so bad.

00:55:55.680 --> 00:56:04.840
[Guest 1]: I just felt shattered, I said, no, we worked so hard for them.

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:08.920
[Guest 1]: And they're not realizing that all I'm trying to make this world better for them, but they

00:56:08.920 --> 00:56:09.920
[Guest 1]: don't understand it.

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:15.000
[Guest 1]: And I felt really hurt to the point of, you know, almost feeling teary.

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:21.440
[Guest 1]: And I hadn't realized that that's how, I hadn't thought that this is what is going to happen

00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:22.440
[Guest 1]: to me in that scene.

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:25.160
[Guest 1]: And that was not even the mandate of the scene.

00:56:25.160 --> 00:56:28.280
[Guest 1]: And that's not even anything that's written in to the scene.

00:56:28.280 --> 00:56:33.440
[Guest 1]: And I don't even know if it shows on screen or it doesn't, but it was a big moment for

00:56:33.440 --> 00:56:34.440
[Guest 1]: me.

00:56:34.440 --> 00:56:41.440
[Guest 1]: That's when I felt like I had begun to believe in the world that I had tried to create.

00:56:41.440 --> 00:56:45.240
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I had a question for later, but it seems a natural follow up question

00:56:45.240 --> 00:56:47.640
[Amit Varma]: now that you've sort of mentioned this moment.

00:56:47.640 --> 00:56:54.400
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask it now, which is that, you know, does immersing yourself in the role also then

00:56:54.400 --> 00:56:57.080
[Amit Varma]: change the person you are and the way you view the world?

00:56:57.080 --> 00:57:01.280
[Amit Varma]: For example, a couple of examples which came to mind from what you've said about your work

00:57:01.280 --> 00:57:06.920
[Amit Varma]: earlier is one of course this, that you felt that Delhi was more of a safe zone because

00:57:06.920 --> 00:57:10.720
[Amit Varma]: you felt more empathetic towards the police once you did the film.

00:57:10.720 --> 00:57:14.640
[Amit Varma]: And the other was you also pointed out that how, you know, playing the role that you did

00:57:14.640 --> 00:57:21.200
[Amit Varma]: in Manto made you more empathetic towards, you know, your naniji and women of the past

00:57:21.200 --> 00:57:27.720
[Amit Varma]: on whom you would otherwise have been judgmental, or when you were sort of a fiery feminist

00:57:27.720 --> 00:57:28.880
[Amit Varma]: in college.

00:57:28.880 --> 00:57:34.320
[Amit Varma]: And so do roles kind of change the way that, you know, you view the world and in some way

00:57:34.320 --> 00:57:35.320
[Amit Varma]: change you as well?

00:57:35.320 --> 00:57:42.120
[Guest 1]: So usually, I actually feel nervous to romanticize the idea of, you know, being immersed in a

00:57:42.120 --> 00:57:49.520
[Guest 1]: role and not being able to come out of it or it affecting you in a big way.

00:57:49.520 --> 00:57:51.640
[Guest 1]: But I have to say that it does.

00:57:51.640 --> 00:57:54.160
[Guest 1]: I have to accept that it does.

00:57:54.160 --> 00:58:00.280
[Guest 1]: And taking the example of Delhi crime, I think it did make me very empathetic to the Delhi

00:58:00.280 --> 00:58:09.760
[Guest 1]: police and especially this time, this year in February, I felt very uncomfortable with

00:58:09.760 --> 00:58:14.200
[Guest 1]: that empathy, you know, and I didn't know what to do with that.

00:58:14.200 --> 00:58:19.240
[Guest 1]: It was almost like the memory of that experience remained and so the empathy with the police

00:58:19.240 --> 00:58:20.240
[Guest 1]: remained.

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:26.720
[Guest 1]: But then I was again seeing things happening from the perspective of a civilian.

00:58:26.720 --> 00:58:31.920
[Guest 1]: And what I was seeing was not making me feel like I should feel any empathy, but yet there

00:58:31.920 --> 00:58:32.920
[Guest 1]: was some empathy.

00:58:32.920 --> 00:58:37.480
[Guest 1]: So that dichotomy was making me very uncomfortable.

00:58:37.480 --> 00:58:43.360
[Guest 1]: And I guess that was proof of the fact that it does stay with you for a while.

00:58:43.360 --> 00:58:50.360
[Guest 1]: But I can't really tell how long it does or does it go away or not or what.

00:58:50.360 --> 00:58:56.120
[Guest 1]: And you know, I've listened to a lot of actors talk about similar experiences and they've

00:58:56.120 --> 00:59:01.320
[Guest 1]: all and what seems to me, seems to be the commonality between what they're saying is

00:59:01.320 --> 00:59:07.240
[Guest 1]: that they don't know where it comes up again, you know, for example, Nicole Kidman was talking

00:59:07.240 --> 00:59:14.440
[Guest 1]: about her role in Big Little Lies, and there's that abusive relationship and which was very,

00:59:14.440 --> 00:59:17.400
[Guest 1]: very beautifully done in the series.

00:59:17.400 --> 00:59:23.680
[Guest 1]: And she said, I didn't know that I was so angry because of playing that role that one

00:59:23.680 --> 00:59:31.400
[Guest 1]: day when I went back from shoot, I took something and shattered the glass in the bathroom.

00:59:31.400 --> 00:59:36.520
[Guest 1]: She said, I am not that person, I don't do this, but this remained with me and I didn't

00:59:36.520 --> 00:59:39.240
[Guest 1]: realize that this was happening to me.

00:59:39.240 --> 00:59:45.840
[Guest 1]: And I think when I shot for Hamid also, months after I'd finished shooting for Hamid, I remember

00:59:45.840 --> 00:59:53.440
[Guest 1]: I was telling Mukul the story of how I watched this documentary in which Parveena Hangar

00:59:53.440 --> 00:59:58.440
[Guest 1]: is talking to the Satya Lady and both are people whose children, whose sons had gone

00:59:58.440 --> 00:59:59.440
[Guest 1]: missing.

00:59:59.440 --> 01:00:05.160
[Guest 1]: They were both 15 years old and I was recounting this moment.

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:10.160
[Guest 1]: And I didn't realize that it had been with me for a while and I was in tears and it had

01:00:10.160 --> 01:00:13.720
[Guest 1]: been about four or five months and I hadn't realized that I was still carrying some of

01:00:13.720 --> 01:00:16.240
[Guest 1]: the grief from there.

01:00:16.240 --> 01:00:20.880
[Guest 1]: But you know, I still, I feel so scared to even admit to this because I feel that as

01:00:20.880 --> 01:00:27.400
[Guest 1]: actors, if you become so conscious of these moments and if you try and seek, if you try

01:00:27.400 --> 01:00:33.120
[Guest 1]: and then recreate magic, it's not going to happen.

01:00:33.120 --> 01:00:40.320
[Guest 1]: So I try as much as possible to not remember this, you know, so that I can be open to ways

01:00:40.320 --> 01:00:46.640
[Guest 1]: of achieving magical moments like these, can be open to new ways of achieving magical moments

01:00:46.640 --> 01:00:47.640
[Guest 1]: like these.

01:00:47.640 --> 01:00:53.640
[Guest 1]: And that I don't then go back to the same way that I did it in, that I happened to find

01:00:53.640 --> 01:00:59.040
[Guest 1]: it in Hamid or happened to find it in Delhi Crime or happened to find it in Kissa.

01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:03.520
[Amit Varma]: And Mokul, I have a sort of related question for you, which is like a really weird question,

01:01:03.520 --> 01:01:05.240
[Amit Varma]: which I can ask only you.

01:01:05.240 --> 01:01:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And you'll realize why when I come to it, which is that in my experience as a poker

01:01:09.560 --> 01:01:15.440
[Amit Varma]: player, I often realized that and non poker players often don't realize the highs and

01:01:15.440 --> 01:01:20.200
[Amit Varma]: lows of emotions that are involved in playing poker, I've often found that poker can really

01:01:20.200 --> 01:01:23.240
[Amit Varma]: bring out the worst elements of your character.

01:01:23.240 --> 01:01:27.200
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, it's a process of self discovery, where you'll act in particular ways where

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:31.280
[Amit Varma]: you're on severe tilt and all of that and later you'll look back and you'll take a step

01:01:31.280 --> 01:01:35.960
[Amit Varma]: outside of yourself and you'll kind of realize that shit, you know, and you learn a little

01:01:35.960 --> 01:01:41.400
[Amit Varma]: bit about yourself also, when you do that in those low moments, and even the high moments,

01:01:41.400 --> 01:01:43.400
[Amit Varma]: where you can overreact to that as well.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:47.720
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that as an actor, part of what you're doing when you're immersing yourself

01:01:47.720 --> 01:01:53.040
[Amit Varma]: in a role is that you are taking a step out of yourself to that meta level where you're

01:01:53.040 --> 01:01:57.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of, you know, as you're immersing yourself in a character, you're also taking that step

01:01:57.560 --> 01:02:01.760
[Amit Varma]: back and looking at sort of the motivations and the emotions and the way this person would

01:02:01.760 --> 01:02:04.000
[Amit Varma]: behave and the way all of that plays.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:10.600
[Amit Varma]: So just in terms of sort of self awareness, does the acting process and I don't know if

01:02:10.600 --> 01:02:15.240
[Amit Varma]: you share my feelings about poker in this context, but does the acting process does

01:02:15.240 --> 01:02:20.660
[Amit Varma]: it lead to at some level, a sort of greater self awareness of your own behaviors and motivations

01:02:20.660 --> 01:02:24.560
[Amit Varma]: and even your own performative actions as it were?

01:02:24.560 --> 01:02:25.560
[Guest 2]: There's a lot there.

01:02:25.560 --> 01:02:30.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, I think this whole thing of I'm going to address first your comparison

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:35.000
[Guest 2]: with you know, those moments in poker when you feel you're in there, and you're sort

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:37.480
[Guest 2]: of observing yourself from the outside.

01:02:37.480 --> 01:02:41.800
[Guest 2]: With acting that happens, but you try and shut it out, because the minute you start

01:02:41.800 --> 01:02:47.200
[Guest 2]: being aware of, of that whole of that, then you might lose that moment also, you know,

01:02:47.200 --> 01:02:52.280
[Guest 2]: if you're very conscious of, because sometimes, I think, I would use a different word for

01:02:52.280 --> 01:02:55.680
[Guest 2]: what Jessica said, you know, when she talked about magic, I say, sometimes you surprise

01:02:55.680 --> 01:02:59.080
[Guest 2]: yourself, you know, sometimes something happens, and you surprise yourself, and, and that feels

01:02:59.080 --> 01:03:00.220
[Guest 2]: really great.

01:03:00.220 --> 01:03:04.720
[Guest 2]: But if you think about it too much, sometimes that actually takes away or ruins the whole

01:03:04.720 --> 01:03:08.480
[Guest 2]: thing, because then you're trying to analyze why that may have happened or what you did.

01:03:08.480 --> 01:03:10.400
[Guest 2]: And that kind of destroys it.

01:03:10.400 --> 01:03:14.160
[Guest 2]: And I think that might relate, I don't know if you relate to that on the poker table.

01:03:14.160 --> 01:03:17.800
[Guest 2]: But you know, sometimes if you're, sometimes you're just in the zone, right, you're doing,

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:19.720
[Guest 2]: you're playing really well, you're figuring things out.

01:03:19.720 --> 01:03:23.360
[Guest 2]: And if you try and analyze it too much as to what am I doing and trying to impose rules

01:03:23.360 --> 01:03:26.080
[Guest 2]: on it, you might just shatter that whole thing for yourself.

01:03:26.080 --> 01:03:30.560
[Guest 2]: I mean, it might work better when you're on tilt to say, I need to get out of the zone.

01:03:30.560 --> 01:03:31.800
[Guest 2]: But that's what I feel.

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:34.800
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's, it's, it's hard to know.

01:03:34.800 --> 01:03:37.280
[Guest 2]: I mean, I see, I look at acting as a sport in some sense, right?

01:03:37.280 --> 01:03:41.280
[Guest 2]: It's hard to know what you're doing, right?

01:03:41.280 --> 01:03:43.000
[Guest 2]: You know, it's very hard to figure that out.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:46.800
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, and to, to answer your earlier question, which you said, you know, which

01:03:46.800 --> 01:03:49.080
[Guest 2]: what are your rules or what are the things you follow?

01:03:49.080 --> 01:03:53.400
[Guest 2]: I think you, you know, you, you try and get certain things in place, you know, certain

01:03:53.400 --> 01:03:59.720
[Guest 2]: routines in place, maybe you learn your lines, you try and see how this character might behave

01:03:59.720 --> 01:04:02.160
[Guest 2]: otherwise or practice in those ways.

01:04:02.160 --> 01:04:05.280
[Guest 2]: So that a lot of the routine is taken care of.

01:04:05.280 --> 01:04:10.680
[Guest 2]: And you allow yourself more chances for something wonderful to happen where you would be closer

01:04:10.680 --> 01:04:15.760
[Guest 2]: to reacting, like maybe the character would react, but how it happens, when it happens,

01:04:15.760 --> 01:04:16.760
[Guest 2]: I don't know.

01:04:16.760 --> 01:04:20.200
[Guest 2]: And at some level, I think I'm, I'm sort of echoing Rasika here, but I say, I don't want

01:04:20.200 --> 01:04:25.760
[Guest 2]: to analyze it too much also, because I sometimes feel that that might take away, you know,

01:04:25.760 --> 01:04:26.760
[Guest 2]: from how that happens.

01:04:26.760 --> 01:04:30.760
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, you try and keep the routines going and it's like, you pull line and length

01:04:30.760 --> 01:04:34.800
[Guest 2]: and you just hope that, you know, the ball, you know, takes the edge, you know, you, you

01:04:34.800 --> 01:04:37.320
[Guest 2]: increase the probability of something going right.

01:04:37.320 --> 01:04:41.320
[Guest 2]: And that's perhaps how I look at it, you know, that you just, you can't, and the other problem,

01:04:41.320 --> 01:04:46.080
[Guest 2]: of course, is that, which is probably negating all that I'm saying is that very often you

01:04:46.080 --> 01:04:50.200
[Guest 2]: have moments when you think, oh my God, I did something fantastic here, you know, like

01:04:50.200 --> 01:04:54.000
[Guest 2]: there was maybe because you surprised yourself and that feels great.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:58.840
[Guest 2]: And when you watch the film or you watch whatever you've shot, you know, months later, and you're

01:04:58.840 --> 01:05:02.120
[Guest 2]: looking for that because you think, oh my God, this was just fantastic, you know, and

01:05:02.120 --> 01:05:05.920
[Guest 2]: even the, and sometimes your co-act also feels it, you know, they feel that we had something

01:05:05.920 --> 01:05:10.400
[Guest 2]: here, this really was something that worked and it looks very ordinary because there's

01:05:10.400 --> 01:05:11.600
[Guest 2]: so much else to it, right?

01:05:11.600 --> 01:05:15.680
[Guest 2]: It's also it's context within the story, how it's edited and everything else.

01:05:15.680 --> 01:05:20.000
[Guest 2]: And there are some other things you see, which you thought were very mundane and they strike

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:22.040
[Guest 2]: you as, oh, that looks really wonderful.

01:05:22.040 --> 01:05:24.520
[Guest 2]: You know, when you didn't really look at it very seriously.

01:05:24.520 --> 01:05:30.240
[Guest 2]: So at some level I've stopped or I try not to get too excited about a moment that I thought

01:05:30.240 --> 01:05:34.560
[Guest 2]: really worked and vice versa, you know, like sometimes, you know, something just looks

01:05:34.560 --> 01:05:36.800
[Guest 2]: fantastic, which you thought was very, you know, you just did it.

01:05:36.800 --> 01:05:40.920
[Guest 2]: It wasn't like a big deal and you didn't feel, you know, it's not like, you know, the co-actor

01:05:40.920 --> 01:05:42.520
[Guest 2]: and you said, oh, wow, that really felt good.

01:05:42.520 --> 01:05:47.360
[Guest 2]: And I think a lot of it is, is that, you know, you surprised yourself, but it may not have

01:05:47.360 --> 01:05:51.360
[Guest 2]: worked or it's not just that it's also on the edit, you know, in the context of the

01:05:51.360 --> 01:05:54.680
[Guest 2]: broader storytelling, it wasn't a big deal, you know?

01:05:54.680 --> 01:05:55.680
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

01:05:55.680 --> 01:05:58.280
[Guest 2]: So I don't know, but that's, that's what I feel about it.

01:05:58.280 --> 01:05:59.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:05:59.280 --> 01:06:00.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:06:00.280 --> 01:06:02.560
[Amit Varma]: No, what I meant was not in the context of in the moment, because in the moment, I'm

01:06:02.560 --> 01:06:06.720
[Amit Varma]: in a Virat Kohli is playing a cover drive and he is self aware of his elbow angle and

01:06:06.720 --> 01:06:09.560
[Amit Varma]: his footwork, obviously, he's going to get out immediately.

01:06:09.560 --> 01:06:13.760
[Amit Varma]: But in a broader sense of when he looks back at why he's been getting out in single digits

01:06:13.760 --> 01:06:16.600
[Amit Varma]: and he says, oh, my stance changed a little bit.

01:06:16.600 --> 01:06:19.080
[Amit Varma]: So the angle of the bat, and that's why I've been edging it.

01:06:19.080 --> 01:06:23.280
[Amit Varma]: And I would just imagine that, you know, one of the things that we don't do as human beings

01:06:23.280 --> 01:06:29.240
[Amit Varma]: too much is examine why we do the things that we do, why we react the things that we do,

01:06:29.240 --> 01:06:31.840
[Amit Varma]: we just kind of live life without thinking about it.

01:06:31.840 --> 01:06:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that acting is one profession, where you are actually required very often

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:43.800
[Amit Varma]: to take a step back and examine a human being, which is this imagined human being whose,

01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:47.860
[Amit Varma]: you know, skin you will inhabit for a while, and think about why they are the way they

01:06:47.860 --> 01:06:50.000
[Amit Varma]: are and why they do the things they do.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:55.640
[Amit Varma]: And would that sort of habit of thinking and a greater self awareness then also percolate

01:06:55.640 --> 01:07:00.640
[Amit Varma]: into other aspects of your life was my sort of broader question.

01:07:00.640 --> 01:07:04.760
[Guest 2]: I think I did a lot of that unnecessarily myself to myself anyway, I would always think

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:06.760
[Guest 2]: why the hell am I behaving like this?

01:07:06.760 --> 01:07:08.480
[Guest 2]: Why am I so angry about something?

01:07:08.480 --> 01:07:10.560
[Guest 2]: And I'm not sure I got the right answer.

01:07:10.560 --> 01:07:13.560
[Guest 2]: So I think I was like that anyway, I would always analyze myself.

01:07:13.560 --> 01:07:19.520
[Guest 2]: But I think your point is well taken that if there is one singular aspect of, you know,

01:07:19.520 --> 01:07:23.160
[Guest 2]: playing or inhabiting a character is that you have to think like that character, obviously,

01:07:23.160 --> 01:07:27.800
[Guest 2]: which is, you know, I mean, and if again, if there's a singular thing that I look at,

01:07:27.800 --> 01:07:32.320
[Guest 2]: and I can clearly say, I think is bad acting or bad performance or bad, you know, depiction

01:07:32.320 --> 01:07:37.640
[Guest 2]: of something is, if I don't believe that the characters believes what they say, you know,

01:07:37.640 --> 01:07:41.640
[Guest 2]: that they must, at all points in time, and that's true for, you know, you'd call it bad

01:07:41.640 --> 01:07:44.920
[Guest 2]: writing, you'd call it bad direction, you call it bad acting and everything else, you

01:07:44.920 --> 01:07:50.520
[Guest 2]: have to inhabit the world of that person, you know, and convince us that you believe

01:07:50.520 --> 01:07:53.800
[Guest 2]: what you say, you know, and why you do what you say, and I think that's probably a reason

01:07:53.800 --> 01:07:59.280
[Guest 2]: why maybe people in the arts, whether they're writers, directors, tend to be a little more

01:07:59.280 --> 01:08:00.280
[Guest 2]: left wing, right?

01:08:00.280 --> 01:08:04.960
[Guest 2]: Because you tend to, I mean, whether you are, you get more empathetic, because you are in

01:08:04.960 --> 01:08:07.960
[Guest 2]: the profession, or whether because you are empathetic, you enter that profession, I don't

01:08:07.960 --> 01:08:09.080
[Guest 2]: know.

01:08:09.080 --> 01:08:15.400
[Guest 2]: But there tends to be that sense of, of identifying with, you know, why other people do what they

01:08:15.400 --> 01:08:16.400
[Guest 2]: do.

01:08:16.400 --> 01:08:18.920
[Guest 2]: And I think that moment that Jessica talked about, you know, empathizing with the Delhi

01:08:18.920 --> 01:08:24.640
[Guest 2]: police was a fantastic one. And I think, despite all that we may try, we are constantly at

01:08:24.640 --> 01:08:30.280
[Guest 2]: a point now in society where we are just losing empathy for a person who's on the other side,

01:08:30.280 --> 01:08:33.920
[Guest 2]: you know, of the political divide, and it's, it doesn't help.

01:08:33.920 --> 01:08:38.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And it seems to me that, you know, great art embraces complexity. And what we find

01:08:38.400 --> 01:08:42.680
[Amit Varma]: in our modern times is that the political discourse is so simplistic and polarized,

01:08:42.680 --> 01:08:47.400
[Amit Varma]: where it is not just necessary to argue that the other side is wrong, but it is necessary

01:08:47.400 --> 01:08:53.080
[Amit Varma]: to paint them as evil. And, you know, that's my sort of big lament about the discourse.

01:08:53.080 --> 01:08:56.680
[Amit Varma]: But before we get carried away into that particular digression, I think we should take a commercial

01:08:56.680 --> 01:09:01.200
[Amit Varma]: break because I promise two dichotomies and having gotten one over with before the break,

01:09:01.200 --> 01:09:06.440
[Amit Varma]: it is only natural that we save the other one for after the break.

