01:10:20.240 --> 01:10:22.920
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen. I'm chatting with Rasika Duggal and Mukul

01:10:22.920 --> 01:10:27.960
[Amit Varma]: Chadha about the acting life and their journey in Mumbai and the entertainment industry here.

01:10:27.960 --> 01:10:33.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the second dichotomy that I sort of mentioned is again, something that's

01:10:33.600 --> 01:10:37.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of been playing out over the course of your careers in the sense, which is more and

01:10:37.680 --> 01:10:42.680
[Amit Varma]: more outsiders coming into the film industry, so to say, like, back in the day, when I first

01:10:42.680 --> 01:10:47.200
[Amit Varma]: came to Mumbai in the 90s, it was a very constricted kind of space, it was a particular kind of

01:10:47.200 --> 01:10:51.600
[Amit Varma]: person in the film industry, another particular kind of person in the TV industry, they had

01:10:51.600 --> 01:10:56.760
[Amit Varma]: their own sort of sensibilities. And in the time that you've been growing in your careers

01:10:56.760 --> 01:11:01.400
[Amit Varma]: here and pursuing that, I mean, just in these 12 years, like you mentioned, Rasika, and

01:11:01.400 --> 01:11:07.160
[Amit Varma]: I suppose a similar period of time for you, Mukul, is that so much has kind of changed.

01:11:07.160 --> 01:11:12.200
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, a lot of that is because of the scope of the work, like I often sort of,

01:11:12.200 --> 01:11:15.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, the analogy that comes to my mind, when I think of what's happened to the entertainment

01:11:15.880 --> 01:11:21.640
[Amit Varma]: industry in Mumbai is the IPL. Because what the IPL did was that before the IPL, when

01:11:21.640 --> 01:11:25.320
[Amit Varma]: it came to cricket, there were a few superstars who would play test cricket and make it to

01:11:25.320 --> 01:11:29.720
[Amit Varma]: the top, but everybody else was basically, there was nothing for them to do, it was just

01:11:29.720 --> 01:11:33.880
[Amit Varma]: lifelong frustration. And it seemed to me that at one point, Bollywood was like that,

01:11:33.880 --> 01:11:39.280
[Amit Varma]: like in the 90s, I remember telling friends of mine about how the cafes are full of people

01:11:39.280 --> 01:11:42.160
[Amit Varma]: who've been struggling for like 20 years, and we'll never get anywhere. And it's so

01:11:42.160 --> 01:11:46.360
[Amit Varma]: sad and poignant. But how that has changed is just in the same way that the IPL sort

01:11:46.360 --> 01:11:51.400
[Amit Varma]: of opened up opportunities for a much wider pool of people. It seems that you know, all

01:11:51.400 --> 01:11:57.040
[Amit Varma]: these web series is coming and just a changing landscape of entertainment has made it easier

01:11:57.040 --> 01:12:03.400
[Amit Varma]: for outsiders like you guys to actually come in and hope to build a career and a body of

01:12:03.400 --> 01:12:09.000
[Amit Varma]: work here. So tell me a little bit about, you know, what was the landscape of the entertainment

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:15.520
[Amit Varma]: industry? When you guys embarked upon these careers? Like, what did it look like then?

01:12:15.520 --> 01:12:19.320
[Amit Varma]: How has it changed? And how have your views of it changed over time?

01:12:19.320 --> 01:12:23.040
[Guest 2]: I think that's a great analogy of given in terms of the IPL. And I think what the OTT

01:12:23.040 --> 01:12:29.040
[Guest 2]: revolution has done for acting or anything related to content creation is absolutely

01:12:29.040 --> 01:12:33.520
[Guest 2]: true. I mean, there's just so much more opportunity for everyone. When I first became an actor,

01:12:33.520 --> 01:12:38.720
[Guest 2]: I don't the landscape was different, no doubt. And I don't think I gave as much thought to

01:12:38.720 --> 01:12:42.040
[Guest 2]: it. It wasn't that well thought out a decision that okay, this is this career makes sense

01:12:42.040 --> 01:12:46.160
[Guest 2]: because the dynamics of this industry are such in fact, if I had done that, I might

01:12:46.160 --> 01:12:50.000
[Guest 2]: not have ever become an actor. I became an actor because I wanted to act you know, I

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:54.160
[Guest 2]: did theater to start with it's improv, which I still do. And then you know, whatever roles

01:12:54.160 --> 01:12:58.120
[Guest 2]: I could get, I would want to do them. But yeah, when you have very singular stories,

01:12:58.120 --> 01:13:02.720
[Guest 2]: which are two hours long, and by definition, you know, it's going to be about one, two

01:13:02.720 --> 01:13:07.080
[Guest 2]: or three protagonists. And in a superstar driven world where you know, the spoils all

01:13:07.080 --> 01:13:11.760
[Guest 2]: the spoils go to a few people, it's very hard for anybody else to break into it. And also,

01:13:11.760 --> 01:13:15.320
[Guest 2]: if you're not going to make a breakthrough at in your early 20s, then you're probably

01:13:15.320 --> 01:13:19.200
[Guest 2]: you know, going to be limited to playing fringe characters, which you know, and it's I mean,

01:13:19.200 --> 01:13:24.800
[Guest 2]: we've seen so many good actors, and I started acting so many wonderful actors I've seen,

01:13:24.800 --> 01:13:29.280
[Guest 2]: spend so much time doing roles on the margins, which don't really, I mean, it's not the length

01:13:29.280 --> 01:13:33.120
[Guest 2]: of the role, but the role doesn't, you know, give bent to, you know, their talent and what

01:13:33.120 --> 01:13:38.520
[Guest 2]: they can do. That is obviously changed with, you know, technology and the OTT platforms,

01:13:38.520 --> 01:13:41.960
[Guest 2]: because it's not just more content coming out, but it's different kinds of stories being

01:13:41.960 --> 01:13:46.160
[Guest 2]: told, where you know, it's such a large cast where you don't have to be the protagonist

01:13:46.160 --> 01:13:51.920
[Guest 2]: of the story to have an interesting, you know, graph. There's so many, you know, characters

01:13:51.920 --> 01:13:55.720
[Guest 2]: who may not be the main leads who have very interesting stories, it's, it's far more novelistic

01:13:55.720 --> 01:14:00.200
[Guest 2]: in its telling, right? I mean, the way the whole thing is done. And that's been wonderful.

01:14:00.200 --> 01:14:03.880
[Guest 2]: I mean, I'm eternally grateful to it. I don't think I mean, the biggest thing that I've

01:14:03.880 --> 01:14:06.800
[Guest 2]: done is the office, I don't think that would have happened. That wouldn't have happened

01:14:06.800 --> 01:14:10.600
[Guest 2]: without the OTT revolution. And I would never have been considered I mean, in fact, the

01:14:10.600 --> 01:14:15.560
[Guest 2]: office is the first show where I was called for an audition to play the lead, I have never

01:14:15.560 --> 01:14:20.480
[Guest 2]: been called for an audition for a lead role before that. Because that just wasn't possible.

01:14:20.480 --> 01:14:24.160
[Guest 2]: I mean, leave aside obviously, some, you know, short films or an ad, because that's totally

01:14:24.160 --> 01:14:30.200
[Guest 2]: a different thing. But you would not even consider it for that part. You know, and this

01:14:30.200 --> 01:14:33.920
[Guest 2]: is the first time you're being considered the fact that someone I mean, I remember the

01:14:33.920 --> 01:14:37.680
[Guest 2]: casting director Kavish called me up and said, we're considering auditioning you for the

01:14:37.680 --> 01:14:42.400
[Guest 2]: lead, would you be interested? And I was like, where is the question in this? You know, obviously,

01:14:42.400 --> 01:14:46.120
[Guest 2]: I would be interested. This is the first time someone's even asking me if I would audition

01:14:46.120 --> 01:14:50.640
[Guest 2]: for the lead part. So that was that's great. And I think it's it's been wonderful. I hope

01:14:50.640 --> 01:14:54.880
[Guest 2]: it continues as long as it can. Because as far as I'm concerned, I think you know, I

01:14:54.880 --> 01:15:00.280
[Guest 2]: just like to do good work. And it just you know, as much of it that can exist is great.

01:15:00.280 --> 01:15:04.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I sort of you know, you sort of preempted a question I was going to ask, but

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:09.240
[Amit Varma]: it's a great observation, which is I'd recently written a post on my newsletter, which was

01:15:09.240 --> 01:15:13.920
[Amit Varma]: called a meditation on form is about how the form in which you write can change what you

01:15:13.920 --> 01:15:17.880
[Amit Varma]: write and therefore can change the writer. For example, you know, blogging gives you

01:15:17.880 --> 01:15:22.160
[Amit Varma]: the freedom to go beyond the dictates of the 800 word op-ed. So you can write an 80 word

01:15:22.160 --> 01:15:26.800
[Amit Varma]: observation or an 8000 word essay. And when you can stretch out like that you are often

01:15:26.800 --> 01:15:31.560
[Amit Varma]: compelled to think deeper like when I do three hour conversations on my podcast, for example,

01:15:31.560 --> 01:15:36.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm compelled to go deeper, you know, give a certain amount of respect to the guests

01:15:36.760 --> 01:15:40.760
[Amit Varma]: because I'm no longer playing, you know, gotcha in a 20 minute interview, which is what so

01:15:40.760 --> 01:15:46.280
[Amit Varma]: much of television is all about. And the form changes not just the content, but it changes

01:15:46.280 --> 01:15:49.760
[Amit Varma]: the writer because of the way that you are then forced to approach it. And what you were

01:15:49.760 --> 01:15:54.440
[Amit Varma]: saying about, you know, the novelistic approach that is now possible. Like I remember one

01:15:54.440 --> 01:15:58.200
[Amit Varma]: of the reasons I was so blown away by the wire when I first saw it was that it was so

01:15:58.200 --> 01:16:02.440
[Amit Varma]: novelistic, you had so many characters who were treated like main characters and the

01:16:02.440 --> 01:16:08.200
[Amit Varma]: stories unfolding leisurely through the many episodes. And it was like an epiphany for

01:16:08.200 --> 01:16:12.240
[Amit Varma]: me that because before that I thought all cinema was really like a short story, not

01:16:12.240 --> 01:16:17.760
[Amit Varma]: like a novel. You had like one linear plotline and a couple of main characters. And my sort

01:16:17.760 --> 01:16:25.240
[Amit Varma]: of question to Rasika also, you know, sort of elaborating upon that is that did this

01:16:25.240 --> 01:16:30.080
[Amit Varma]: and I'm sure that this form changed the kind of stories and the kind of characters and

01:16:30.080 --> 01:16:34.760
[Amit Varma]: is that something that you saw changing? Like I recently saw an interview of Shweta Tripathi

01:16:34.760 --> 01:16:38.240
[Amit Varma]: where she said this thing which kind of moved me, which is she was asked about what her

01:16:38.240 --> 01:16:43.280
[Amit Varma]: dream roles were. And she said that look, all my dream roles are roles, whenever I think

01:16:43.280 --> 01:16:47.280
[Amit Varma]: of something that's a dream role to me is something that's been played by a man. You

01:16:47.280 --> 01:16:52.760
[Amit Varma]: know, none of this roles that women play are things that I would necessarily aspire to.

01:16:52.760 --> 01:16:56.600
[Amit Varma]: And I remember Seema Pawar also saying somewhere that listen, where are the films that are

01:16:56.600 --> 01:17:02.880
[Amit Varma]: dealing with the issues of women past 50? That there is still a landscape of possibility

01:17:02.880 --> 01:17:07.040
[Amit Varma]: open out there, especially when it comes to female characters. I mean, looking at your

01:17:07.040 --> 01:17:10.680
[Amit Varma]: work, obviously, you've, you know, gotten the opportunity to create strong characters

01:17:10.680 --> 01:17:16.560
[Amit Varma]: and you made them your own. But just looking at that sort of landscape in general, as it

01:17:16.560 --> 01:17:21.480
[Amit Varma]: is evolving, is the lament premature because things are changing in the right direction?

01:17:21.480 --> 01:17:25.840
[Amit Varma]: Or is it something that you think is, you know, still a problem that the sort of the

01:17:25.840 --> 01:17:32.200
[Amit Varma]: scope of the roles that someone like you gets is not as vast as the scope that a comparable

01:17:32.200 --> 01:17:33.600
[Guest 1]: male actor might get?

01:17:33.600 --> 01:17:41.280
[Guest 1]: I think that the scope is not as vast still, but it's much better than earlier. So in that

01:17:41.280 --> 01:17:48.040
[Guest 1]: sense, yeah, the long form storytelling has helped that because otherwise, the first victim

01:17:48.040 --> 01:17:55.600
[Guest 1]: of a script edit would be the female character. And that was something which was making it

01:17:55.600 --> 01:18:00.800
[Guest 1]: very difficult for people like me to get any interesting parts to play, you know, because

01:18:00.800 --> 01:18:05.960
[Guest 1]: unless you're the female lead of something, and even the female lead in a mainstream Bollywood

01:18:05.960 --> 01:18:13.280
[Guest 1]: film doesn't have much to do as, as we know. But, for example, when Mirzapur was offered

01:18:13.280 --> 01:18:19.400
[Guest 1]: to me, and I remember I read the script. And at that time, I had already shot for Mentor.

01:18:19.400 --> 01:18:24.040
[Guest 1]: So Karan Anshuman, who was one of the directors of season one, he said, you know, I don't

01:18:24.040 --> 01:18:29.000
[Guest 1]: know if you want to do this, because you're doing a female lead, so to say, in a in a

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:35.400
[Guest 1]: film. So I don't know if you want to do this. And when I read the script, I said, I thought

01:18:35.400 --> 01:18:40.360
[Guest 1]: to myself, this is a great part. And especially for me to experiment with something like this,

01:18:40.360 --> 01:18:44.920
[Guest 1]: it's not a part that I would normally get cast in. If they were thinking of it, stereotypically,

01:18:44.920 --> 01:18:49.800
[Guest 1]: they might have gotten somebody who had done roles like that, or had had a different body

01:18:49.800 --> 01:18:53.280
[Guest 1]: type or something like that. So I was very excited about it. But I remember thinking

01:18:53.280 --> 01:18:57.520
[Guest 1]: if this was a film, I would have been really nervous about this character because she would

01:18:57.520 --> 01:19:03.200
[Guest 1]: have probably not had any space. But because this is a series, there is room for her to

01:19:03.200 --> 01:19:08.640
[Guest 1]: exist. You know, I've noticed that even very well meaning films where the director might

01:19:08.640 --> 01:19:13.880
[Guest 1]: want to really give attention to a character finally, when you edit the film, and you have

01:19:13.880 --> 01:19:19.160
[Guest 1]: to keep it a certain length and all of that, the female character suffers a lot. It didn't

01:19:19.160 --> 01:19:24.200
[Guest 1]: happen in Manto because Nandita really would really wanted to make something of Safiya.

01:19:24.200 --> 01:19:29.680
[Guest 1]: And in fact, Safiya was, what was on screen was more than what was on paper. But I've

01:19:29.680 --> 01:19:34.320
[Guest 1]: noticed that it's happened in several other films. So yeah, the OTT space has definitely

01:19:34.320 --> 01:19:41.120
[Guest 1]: given room for many more characters and therefore female characters. But of course, if there

01:19:41.120 --> 01:19:46.040
[Guest 1]: was room only for three, then who would that have gone to? Would those be male characters

01:19:46.040 --> 01:19:51.000
[Guest 1]: or female characters? That's something that we don't know. But also, I feel that in a

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:56.720
[Guest 1]: lot of because feminism is fashionable, and I'm okay to take it even if it's just fashionable,

01:19:56.720 --> 01:20:01.280
[Guest 1]: you know, I'll take that anyway. You know, that's, I think that's still a positive thing.

01:20:01.280 --> 01:20:07.480
[Guest 1]: But a lot of characters that are written for women are sort of, I mean, I don't know how

01:20:07.480 --> 01:20:12.240
[Guest 1]: to describe it. But a lot of times, if it's a female character who's spearheading a show

01:20:12.240 --> 01:20:18.200
[Guest 1]: or a film, the character is almost written in a masculine way, you know. So that's something

01:20:18.200 --> 01:20:23.280
[Guest 1]: that I'm uncomfortable with. And it's not really celebrating femininity, you know. And

01:20:23.280 --> 01:20:30.200
[Guest 1]: but I think the OTT space has sort of done away with a lot of that. Like Shivali's character

01:20:30.200 --> 01:20:35.240
[Guest 1]: in Delhi Grime, you know, to write a story on somebody like Chhaya Sharma, I mean, based

01:20:35.240 --> 01:20:39.920
[Guest 1]: on Chhaya Sharma, and that's a good thing. So I think the OTT space has done away with

01:20:39.920 --> 01:20:47.360
[Guest 1]: a lot of that. In films, I don't know. I think the moment time becomes a limitation, then

01:20:47.360 --> 01:20:52.640
[Guest 1]: the female characters become, get, suffer a lot.

01:20:52.640 --> 01:20:57.760
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sort of just thinking aloud here. But you know, when I was watching Mirzapur,

01:20:57.760 --> 01:21:01.840
[Amit Varma]: one I think is profoundly impressive how you did a role that is so different from what

01:21:01.840 --> 01:21:07.200
[Amit Varma]: you normally do. And you know, where you are required to sort of communicate, you know,

01:21:07.200 --> 01:21:12.040
[Amit Varma]: smouldering sexuality with just a look or a gesture and is both minimal and so effective

01:21:12.040 --> 01:21:15.760
[Amit Varma]: at the same time. So that was very impressive. But the other thing that sort of struck me,

01:21:15.760 --> 01:21:22.760
[Amit Varma]: which has nothing to sort of do with you is that one tendency that I've noticed in Bollywood,

01:21:22.760 --> 01:21:28.120
[Amit Varma]: especially among younger directors over the last 10-15 years or so is, and probably in

01:21:28.120 --> 01:21:35.080
[Amit Varma]: a sense started with, you know, Anurag Kashyap and all, is this sort of macho stylism, where

01:21:35.080 --> 01:21:41.200
[Amit Varma]: you'll have these sort of very stylized set pieces with a lot of violence and a lot of

01:21:41.200 --> 01:21:47.960
[Amit Varma]: this whole sort of, you know, rustic machoness and all of that. And even in Mirzapur, I kind

01:21:47.960 --> 01:21:52.520
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, the gratuitous violence of the, you know, the first scenes and, you know,

01:21:52.520 --> 01:21:55.960
[Amit Varma]: even later, where it's kind of predictable that, you know, the kattai is going to explode

01:21:55.960 --> 01:21:59.600
[Amit Varma]: in the second hand of that character, and they're going to show a bit of the ear or

01:21:59.600 --> 01:22:03.960
[Amit Varma]: the bit of the hand of the thing and the car drives over it. And it seems very, you know,

01:22:03.960 --> 01:22:08.920
[Amit Varma]: gratuitous and stylized and almost for his own sake. And a couple of related questions

01:22:08.920 --> 01:22:12.840
[Amit Varma]: here, and I don't know if you've thought about them. And one of them is that does it sometimes

01:22:12.840 --> 01:22:20.040
[Amit Varma]: happen that the success of a particular sort of style, like, you know, to go back to literature,

01:22:20.040 --> 01:22:24.120
[Amit Varma]: people often say that one of the problems with Salman Rushdie winning the Booker for

01:22:24.120 --> 01:22:28.840
[Amit Varma]: Midnight's Children is that everyone tried writing like him. So for the next two or three

01:22:28.840 --> 01:22:33.400
[Amit Varma]: decades, you had young Indian writers who are writing in expressionistic prose, not

01:22:33.400 --> 01:22:37.160
[Amit Varma]: nearly as well as Rushdie and that kind of, you know, got in the way of literature. So

01:22:37.160 --> 01:22:43.080
[Amit Varma]: looking at cinema, my, you know, untrained observation from an outsider's eye, is that

01:22:43.080 --> 01:22:48.440
[Amit Varma]: something similar seems to have happened with this kind of sort of macho stylism, to repeat

01:22:48.440 --> 01:22:52.880
[Amit Varma]: that term, sort of having worked in a particular phase of Bollywood, and then everyone kind

01:22:52.880 --> 01:22:58.040
[Amit Varma]: of repeats it, and it's very clever, and it makes you feel whatever, but very often the

01:22:58.040 --> 01:23:02.720
[Amit Varma]: whole is less than the sum of its parts. And you have all these beautiful, clever set pieces,

01:23:02.720 --> 01:23:06.480
[Amit Varma]: which don't really add up to something. So my first question is that, do you think that

01:23:06.480 --> 01:23:10.760
[Amit Varma]: there has been something like this, and it is kind of just serendipitous that a certain

01:23:10.760 --> 01:23:15.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of film happened to become successful at a certain time, and then everybody imitated

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:20.080
[Amit Varma]: it? Or was it necessarily going to happen anyway? Because this is how people think.

01:23:20.080 --> 01:23:25.480
[Amit Varma]: And the other question taking off from what, you know, Rasika was saying was that, you

01:23:25.480 --> 01:23:32.680
[Amit Varma]: know, is this one reason why women characters are often written as if from the male gaze,

01:23:32.680 --> 01:23:37.960
[Amit Varma]: in these sort of narrow ways? You know, are there, you know, enough women writers out

01:23:37.960 --> 01:23:42.160
[Amit Varma]: there? And, you know, is that also changing? I mean, I know, I'm rambling a little bit,

01:23:42.160 --> 01:23:44.280
[Amit Varma]: but what are your thoughts on these?

01:23:44.280 --> 01:23:52.320
[Guest 1]: So, you know, in films, and especially when something gets mainstream attention, and is

01:23:52.320 --> 01:23:57.720
[Guest 1]: successful, in terms of numbers at the box office, it happens that there's a trend of

01:23:57.720 --> 01:24:02.840
[Guest 1]: the same kind of films of the same genre, like horror comedy, for example, has been

01:24:02.840 --> 01:24:08.760
[Guest 1]: something which has been working, you know. So, and I think that, especially in terms

01:24:08.760 --> 01:24:13.800
[Guest 1]: of film distribution and film production, there's so much money involved that people

01:24:13.800 --> 01:24:19.280
[Guest 1]: are always tend to follow formula, whatever the formula is at that time. And that I feel

01:24:19.280 --> 01:24:27.160
[Guest 1]: happens a lot in films. I'm very pleasantly surprised and grateful that I don't feel that's

01:24:27.160 --> 01:24:34.760
[Guest 1]: happening in the OTT space. I feel that there is room for different genres to coexist, like

01:24:34.760 --> 01:24:40.640
[Guest 1]: a Maid in Heaven and a Mirzapur, totally different, and very successful, you know. And I don't

01:24:40.640 --> 01:24:47.000
[Guest 1]: even know, either the people at the platforms are picking very carefully, or, and doing

01:24:47.000 --> 01:24:53.040
[Guest 1]: a very good job, or finally, writing because of the long form nature of the content on

01:24:53.040 --> 01:24:58.240
[Guest 1]: OTT space, writing is finally getting the importance that it needed to get all this

01:24:58.240 --> 01:25:04.440
[Guest 1]: file. So there are many interesting, new writers, who are writing very interesting content,

01:25:04.440 --> 01:25:10.000
[Guest 1]: which is why it's getting made. Or the third thing is that there is no declaration of numbers.

01:25:10.000 --> 01:25:15.080
[Guest 1]: Therefore, we might think that both are successful, but maybe one is more successful than the

01:25:15.080 --> 01:25:20.280
[Guest 1]: other and we don't know it, you know. I think whatever the reasons is, it's great, because

01:25:20.280 --> 01:25:27.280
[Guest 1]: I feel like a multiplicity of genres are happening in the OTT space and original Indian content,

01:25:27.280 --> 01:25:32.080
[Guest 1]: like a Panchayat is different from Maid in Heaven, is different from Patal Lok, is different

01:25:32.080 --> 01:25:36.800
[Guest 1]: from Delhi Crime, even though Patal Lok and Delhi Crime can be sort of, I mean, I wouldn't

01:25:36.800 --> 01:25:43.080
[Guest 1]: really describe Patal Lok as just a police procedural, you know, it's, it's, it's an,

01:25:43.080 --> 01:25:49.480
[Guest 1]: in my opinion, epic show. It's like, and Delhi Crime can be possibly described as a police

01:25:49.480 --> 01:25:54.360
[Guest 1]: procedural. So I think there's lots of different stuff happening. And a lot of viewers are

01:25:54.360 --> 01:25:57.920
[Guest 1]: watching them. I don't know the exact numbers. And I'm very happy that we don't know the

01:25:57.920 --> 01:26:02.160
[Guest 1]: numbers, because I think that's really helping keep this space non-formulaic.

01:26:02.160 --> 01:26:06.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a that's a very interesting observation about how a little thing like not knowing

01:26:06.920 --> 01:26:12.120
[Amit Varma]: the numbers can, you know, stop the industry from kind of getting into a rut. And so I

01:26:12.120 --> 01:26:15.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of teach this writing course where I talk a little bit about Shakespeare as well.

01:26:15.840 --> 01:26:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And I keep saying that if Shakespeare lived in modern times, he would, of course, be at

01:26:19.000 --> 01:26:23.000
[Amit Varma]: the top of the entertainment world, because he was, you know, the Spielberg plus the Yash

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:27.520
[Amit Varma]: Chopra of his times. And it strikes me now that the most exciting form he would find

01:26:27.520 --> 01:26:32.040
[Amit Varma]: is the OTT form, because that's where you can really stretch out and build these long

01:26:32.040 --> 01:26:36.080
[Amit Varma]: epic narratives like, you know, Patal Lok, of course, you're right, is a sociological

01:26:36.080 --> 01:26:43.080
[Amit Varma]: epic in a sense, much more than just a police procedural. I want to sort of now talk a little

01:26:43.080 --> 01:26:48.280
[Amit Varma]: bit about the acting life as you've experienced it in the sense that another thing that kind

01:26:48.280 --> 01:26:53.280
[Amit Varma]: of strikes me is, and especially maybe it's changing now, but especially going back 10

01:26:53.280 --> 01:26:58.160
[Amit Varma]: years, 12 years more than that, is that as you were, you know, progressing through your

01:26:58.160 --> 01:27:03.080
[Amit Varma]: acting career, there must have been a terrible scarcity of good roles that you could really

01:27:03.080 --> 01:27:08.240
[Amit Varma]: get your teeth into. So does that sometimes lead to self doubt about am I good enough?

01:27:08.240 --> 01:27:13.160
[Amit Varma]: What am I doing here? Does it lead to a frustration about the choice of career where you say,

01:27:13.160 --> 01:27:20.320
[Amit Varma]: okay, you know, acting, but this is not the time, ecosystem is not developed enough. How

01:27:20.320 --> 01:27:24.520
[Amit Varma]: do you sort of deal with those frustrations? Do you feel yourself compelled to take offers

01:27:24.520 --> 01:27:29.240
[Amit Varma]: of roles that might not otherwise excite you or you might not take in an ideal world, but

01:27:29.240 --> 01:27:34.240
[Amit Varma]: you're like, you know, I have to keep working, I have to kind of keep the fires burning.

01:27:34.240 --> 01:27:39.840
[Amit Varma]: And I guess this is perhaps exacerbated because you are both actors, right? So if one of you

01:27:39.840 --> 01:27:44.080
[Amit Varma]: was a banker, as one of you once was, then, you know, you don't have to kind of worry

01:27:44.080 --> 01:27:48.280
[Amit Varma]: about stability and all of those things. But you're both actors in Bandra. And it's, it's

01:27:48.280 --> 01:27:52.840
[Amit Varma]: not an easy life. How has that sort of journey been like for you guys?

01:27:52.840 --> 01:27:55.840
[Guest 2]: I don't think it was that long ago. I mean, not even don't have to go back 10, 12 years.

01:27:55.840 --> 01:28:00.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, I think, you know, in any case, I think, I don't know of any actor who hasn't

01:28:00.920 --> 01:28:04.600
[Guest 2]: gone through a lot of self doubt. And I think it's something that's endemic to the process.

01:28:04.600 --> 01:28:09.920
[Guest 2]: You're constantly, you know, and also the way it works, which is also why I like what

01:28:09.920 --> 01:28:15.720
[Guest 2]: we do, because, you know, you don't, it's not easy to rest on your laurels, you know,

01:28:15.720 --> 01:28:18.680
[Guest 2]: you kind of, you're starting from scratch again, which is true for many things. But

01:28:18.680 --> 01:28:25.520
[Guest 2]: I think it's more so here, like, you can still go and do a really bad job, what you're doing.

01:28:25.520 --> 01:28:31.080
[Guest 2]: And acting is also a confidence play, right? Very often when you are in an environment

01:28:31.080 --> 01:28:36.240
[Guest 2]: when you don't have the confidence, and maybe the director or the co-actors don't look at

01:28:36.240 --> 01:28:41.760
[Guest 2]: you a certain way, it's sometimes harder to perform well as well. And so self doubt is

01:28:41.760 --> 01:28:46.240
[Guest 2]: a huge part of the process, you can come home on a day and think, I'm a shit actor, I don't

01:28:46.240 --> 01:28:50.200
[Guest 2]: know why I'm even doing this. And then of course, there's the career problems, which

01:28:50.200 --> 01:28:55.280
[Guest 2]: is that, you know, if I look back, I think there are a number of times when I have felt,

01:28:55.280 --> 01:28:58.480
[Guest 2]: why am I doing this, I should just, you know, quit and do something else. And in my case,

01:28:58.480 --> 01:29:03.000
[Guest 2]: it was probably exacerbated by the fact that I had these other interests. So I was constantly

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:06.520
[Guest 2]: dabbling in other things. And, you know, you'd always fool yourself, you know, I'm actually

01:29:06.520 --> 01:29:10.480
[Guest 2]: doing this part time, I'm doing that, I could do this, I could do this. But yes, I think

01:29:10.480 --> 01:29:16.400
[Guest 2]: it's the hardest thing when people who want to be actors ask, you know, they're very excited

01:29:16.400 --> 01:29:21.000
[Guest 2]: now, because it seems like an exciting time. I think this is the hardest part is, you know,

01:29:21.000 --> 01:29:24.560
[Guest 2]: dealing with your own demons and fighting that self doubt, because that is happens all

01:29:24.560 --> 01:29:30.560
[Guest 2]: the time. We are right now in a golden era. But I just feel that this can also change,

01:29:30.560 --> 01:29:34.640
[Guest 2]: right? This is also a gold rush for Indian web series and OTT platforms. There are so

01:29:34.640 --> 01:29:39.320
[Guest 2]: many of them that can also change in time, you never know what may happen. While this

01:29:39.320 --> 01:29:43.880
[Guest 2]: the going is good, let's go for it. But it's wholly possible that, you know, sometime in

01:29:43.880 --> 01:29:51.040
[Guest 2]: the future, one once again, you know, doubts what one is doing. And one does, this is,

01:29:51.040 --> 01:29:55.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, what we should continue doing. And it's probably too late for you to go back

01:29:55.240 --> 01:30:00.760
[Amit Varma]: into banking. So there you go. Though, I should tell our listeners that just last year, Mukul

01:30:00.760 --> 01:30:05.800
[Amit Varma]: and I as part of a team called Haryana Hawks won Poker's version of the IPL. So maybe there

01:30:05.800 --> 01:30:11.960
[Amit Varma]: is a hope for us yet if acting and podcasting both kind of go out of fashion. Rasika is

01:30:11.960 --> 01:30:16.400
[Amit Varma]: laughing, but I don't think she's internally pleased at the thought of Mukul becoming a

01:30:16.400 --> 01:30:24.280
[Guest 1]: more regular poker player. I was very excited about that idea. I thought it was a great

01:30:24.280 --> 01:30:28.400
[Guest 1]: thing. I was more interested about how can you stay up all night? How can you play? How

01:30:28.400 --> 01:30:33.080
[Guest 1]: do you concentrate? And I was very impressed that he used to read books on it. So I was

01:30:33.080 --> 01:30:40.400
[Guest 1]: fully encouraging it. And the certificate, right? Oh, yes. I was very pleased. Like a

01:30:40.400 --> 01:30:44.600
[Guest 1]: good middle class person. I was extremely pleased when he would come back home with

01:30:44.600 --> 01:30:50.120
[Guest 1]: a certificate which said that he'd won something. I was like, nothing else matters. This certificate

01:30:50.120 --> 01:30:55.760
[Guest 1]: is the best thing. I framed it also and put it up very embarrassingly.

01:30:55.760 --> 01:31:00.040
[Guest 2]: I remember the first tournament I think I won or I placed in and I came back and I wanted

01:31:00.040 --> 01:31:03.760
[Guest 2]: to tell Rasika that, you know, I won some money and she was not concerned about that

01:31:03.760 --> 01:31:08.320
[Guest 2]: at all. She's like, but you got a certificate. She was very excited about that aspect.

01:31:08.320 --> 01:31:13.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I still have my trophies up on the top of my shelf out there. No, Rasika, I don't

01:31:13.680 --> 01:31:18.240
[Amit Varma]: think then Mukul plays enough because there is a term that people use called poker widows

01:31:18.240 --> 01:31:24.160
[Amit Varma]: and poker widows are people who have lost their husbands to poker, basically. In the

01:31:24.160 --> 01:31:27.600
[Amit Varma]: sense they haven't died. They're not literally widows but poker widows because they've lost

01:31:27.600 --> 01:31:32.800
[Amit Varma]: their husbands to poker there. So that thankfully does not seem to have been the case here.

01:31:32.800 --> 01:31:37.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, following up from, you know, what Mukul was sort of talking about, Rasika, you've

01:31:37.600 --> 01:31:42.000
[Amit Varma]: once mentioned that, you know, when you got into acting, you wanted to do good work for

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:45.920
[Amit Varma]: its own sake, you were just passionate about the work. And in the beginning, you didn't

01:31:45.920 --> 01:31:49.880
[Amit Varma]: really care about recognition. But then when Kisa came out, you were like, shit is such

01:31:49.880 --> 01:31:54.920
[Amit Varma]: a good film, and I want more people to watch it. And then you do actually feel bad that

01:31:54.920 --> 01:31:59.960
[Amit Varma]: it's not getting the kind of reach it is enough people aren't watching it, and so on and so

01:31:59.960 --> 01:32:06.320
[Amit Varma]: forth. How does that sort of conflict work out? Because on the one hand, we do this because

01:32:06.320 --> 01:32:09.760
[Amit Varma]: we love it. You guys act because you love acting, you're in love with the craft, you're

01:32:09.760 --> 01:32:14.720
[Amit Varma]: in love with that whole journey. But at the same time, we are human beings, and we crave

01:32:14.720 --> 01:32:19.160
[Amit Varma]: validation. And sometimes these two don't go together, where the you know, the kind

01:32:19.160 --> 01:32:25.080
[Amit Varma]: of mainstream work which might have a greater probability to speak in poker terms of getting

01:32:25.080 --> 01:32:30.000
[Amit Varma]: us validation is not the kind of work we want to do or which excites us. So how does sort

01:32:30.000 --> 01:32:34.440
[Amit Varma]: of one deal with this internal conflict? Is this an issue that you faced?

01:32:34.440 --> 01:32:40.680
[Guest 1]: It was not actually, you know, the validation was not so much in terms of numbers. Yeah,

01:32:40.680 --> 01:32:46.200
[Guest 1]: I didn't have so many people writing to me early on in my career, saying that, oh, we

01:32:46.200 --> 01:32:50.080
[Guest 1]: really like your work or anything like that, because they hadn't seen it or the roles were

01:32:50.080 --> 01:32:56.960
[Guest 1]: too small. So in terms of numbers, yeah, the validation was not so much. But I was lucky

01:32:56.960 --> 01:33:04.360
[Guest 1]: to have got a lot of validation for my acting work from the film fraternity since Kshay,

01:33:04.360 --> 01:33:08.840
[Guest 1]: which was like the small indie film that I had done. And actually, there were a lot of

01:33:08.840 --> 01:33:14.240
[Guest 1]: people who were very encouraging at the time that I was doing very small parts in films

01:33:14.240 --> 01:33:19.680
[Guest 1]: as well. You know, so I was always if I had, I had done a two scene role, for example,

01:33:19.680 --> 01:33:24.680
[Guest 1]: in No Smoking. And there were so many people who I got to meet there, who were working

01:33:24.680 --> 01:33:30.680
[Guest 1]: with Anurag at that time. And then those people would constantly recommend me to other work.

01:33:30.680 --> 01:33:36.240
[Guest 1]: So that kind of validation was always there. And that sort of kept me going. I had not

01:33:36.240 --> 01:33:44.480
[Guest 1]: even imagined the idea of having a fan following or people recognizing me. You know, those

01:33:44.480 --> 01:33:50.520
[Guest 1]: were not things that were part of my work culture or not things that people around me

01:33:50.520 --> 01:33:57.240
[Guest 1]: spoke about. Very often, the conversations around me were more about, you know, what

01:33:57.240 --> 01:34:01.400
[Guest 1]: is the kind of work that you're doing? What is the length of the role? Who are you working

01:34:01.400 --> 01:34:07.760
[Guest 1]: with in terms of, you know, the style of the director and not the bigness of the production

01:34:07.760 --> 01:34:11.960
[Guest 1]: house? You know, so, so I think those were the things that were happening around me.

01:34:11.960 --> 01:34:19.040
[Guest 1]: So I didn't really imagine a scenario where I would have validation, have janta validation,

01:34:19.040 --> 01:34:25.640
[Guest 1]: you know, that is not something that I had imagined. So therefore, whatever came was

01:34:25.640 --> 01:34:30.880
[Guest 1]: a bonus. And so I was always thrilled by that rather than feeling bad about how it could

01:34:30.880 --> 01:34:36.880
[Guest 1]: have been. But the only point that you're right, I felt a little let down was the time

01:34:36.880 --> 01:34:42.800
[Guest 1]: that Kista had released and that's because Kista had only two screens in Bombay. It released

01:34:42.800 --> 01:34:48.640
[Guest 1]: in two cinema halls in Bombay, you know. So that was shattering because it was, it was

01:34:48.640 --> 01:34:55.000
[Guest 1]: released so poorly, right? And once yeah, something has got attention, then it becomes

01:34:55.000 --> 01:35:00.280
[Guest 1]: difficult if something else that you do doesn't get the same kind of attention. But all that

01:35:00.280 --> 01:35:05.280
[Guest 1]: has been so recent in my life that I have, I think I still haven't gotten over celebrating

01:35:05.280 --> 01:35:11.040
[Guest 1]: that and I'm still not in the phase. But yeah, like the kind of validation that, the kind

01:35:11.040 --> 01:35:16.440
[Guest 1]: of fan following, I won't even say validation, the kind of fan following that Mirzapur had.

01:35:16.440 --> 01:35:20.760
[Guest 1]: If another show doesn't get that, I'm like, Oh my God, is it not as popular as Mirzapur?

01:35:20.760 --> 01:35:25.640
[Guest 1]: Because once I've tasted that, I do feel like it would be nice to maintain it. But it was

01:35:25.640 --> 01:35:32.160
[Guest 1]: not something in the years that I was looking for work or not getting enough work. It was

01:35:32.160 --> 01:35:37.280
[Guest 1]: not something that preoccupied me at all. Because it was not the kind of conversations

01:35:37.280 --> 01:35:42.320
[Guest 1]: that people around me were also having. It was a very, and I think a lot of actors who

01:35:42.320 --> 01:35:49.080
[Guest 1]: I acted with in theatre at that time, who are now celebrities, so to say, in the OTT

01:35:49.080 --> 01:35:54.440
[Guest 1]: space, all of us joke about it once in a while, you know, we're like, okay, forget about the

01:35:54.440 --> 01:35:59.560
[Guest 1]: theatre mentality, you've become a star now. That kind of thing. Because none of us used

01:35:59.560 --> 01:36:02.760
[Guest 1]: to think like that or talk like that.

01:36:02.760 --> 01:36:06.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, earlier you pointed out, you know, how if something is successful, there's

01:36:06.440 --> 01:36:10.080
[Amit Varma]: so much money riding in the entertainment industry that that almost becomes a formula

01:36:10.080 --> 01:36:13.920
[Amit Varma]: and people want to keep repeating that. And it strikes me that even in the context of

01:36:13.920 --> 01:36:18.280
[Amit Varma]: acting, when a good actor gets into the skin of a character and plays it so well that it

01:36:18.280 --> 01:36:22.880
[Amit Varma]: seems that you know, that is who they are, you know, is there then a danger of getting

01:36:22.880 --> 01:36:28.840
[Amit Varma]: typecast and getting the same kind of sort of roles offered to you? And obviously, Rasika,

01:36:28.840 --> 01:36:32.760
[Amit Varma]: you've, you know, played sort of a variety of roles by now in very different kind of

01:36:32.760 --> 01:36:37.600
[Amit Varma]: projects. So people know that's not the case. But in the early part of your arc, is that

01:36:37.600 --> 01:36:44.040
[Amit Varma]: a worry? And also, you know, in a recent interview, Manav Kaul kind of pointed out about how the

01:36:44.040 --> 01:36:49.920
[Amit Varma]: term actor sort of has a secondary status to the term star, you know, that we are still

01:36:49.920 --> 01:36:54.880
[Amit Varma]: in a, in an industry which worships stars, and actors are almost like second class citizens

01:36:54.880 --> 01:37:00.760
[Amit Varma]: that ONC character role karwa denge and whatever. And I'm assuming that must have changed massively

01:37:00.760 --> 01:37:07.600
[Amit Varma]: over the last few years. But you know, what's your experience of that been like?

01:37:07.600 --> 01:37:11.800
[Guest 2]: I think typecast is something that happens all the time. And you know, I find it's not

01:37:11.800 --> 01:37:16.960
[Guest 2]: just casting directors who do it, but I noticed that it happens with even friends of ours.

01:37:16.960 --> 01:37:21.120
[Guest 2]: And that's when you realize that this is true. People think of you as something because they,

01:37:21.120 --> 01:37:25.560
[Guest 2]: you know, see you do that. I remember, you know, there was a time I was doing a lot of

01:37:25.560 --> 01:37:30.560
[Guest 2]: ads, and Rasika was doing a film, and she would get no ads, and she would wonder why

01:37:30.560 --> 01:37:34.800
[Guest 2]: and I would get no films. And it's the same casting directors would call us, but they

01:37:34.800 --> 01:37:38.520
[Guest 2]: would when they had an ad role, they would call me and they would, you know, and they

01:37:38.520 --> 01:37:44.000
[Guest 2]: wouldn't think of it the other way, because it's just that yeah, I think I yeah, for me,

01:37:44.000 --> 01:37:48.320
[Guest 2]: I always found that, you know, I got slotted into which did wonders for me in terms of

01:37:48.320 --> 01:37:58.160
[Guest 2]: doing a whole bunch of ads. But in terms of this corporate guy, right? I mean, like, I'm

01:37:58.160 --> 01:38:03.800
[Guest 2]: almost negative towards it when I get a call, and I hear that the guy works in a corporate

01:38:03.800 --> 01:38:08.080
[Guest 2]: office, my antenna go up, I immediately think this must be some ridiculous role that they're

01:38:08.080 --> 01:38:13.480
[Guest 2]: calling me for, because I'm going to school, you know, they're calling my number up. And

01:38:13.480 --> 01:38:16.680
[Guest 2]: sometimes the role could be interesting, but I'm just sort of, you know, very to begin

01:38:16.680 --> 01:38:23.160
[Guest 2]: with. And yeah, I think it's an endeavor on my part to try and do as varied roles as possible,

01:38:23.160 --> 01:38:27.320
[Guest 2]: because luckily, we're in a time where that's possible, but there's this, you know, there's

01:38:27.320 --> 01:38:32.360
[Guest 2]: so much more demand now that hopefully, you can try and experiment a little bit and try

01:38:32.360 --> 01:38:36.680
[Guest 2]: and push yourself. And I'm trying to do that. Now there's some projects I'm working on,

01:38:36.680 --> 01:38:40.040
[Guest 2]: which are, you know, trying to break away and do something totally different. And you

01:38:40.040 --> 01:38:43.360
[Guest 2]: find that I mean, you find that with, you know, with casting directors, you keep telling

01:38:43.360 --> 01:38:48.200
[Guest 2]: them, you know, like, for example, I did a show last year, you know, a small part in

01:38:48.200 --> 01:38:52.200
[Guest 2]: a Balaji show, and the casting guy who cast me for office said, he was watching, he said,

01:38:52.200 --> 01:38:55.200
[Guest 2]: I was wondering how you're doing it, because I couldn't think of you as anybody but Jagdeep

01:38:55.200 --> 01:38:59.680
[Guest 2]: Chandra. And you feel bad because you feel like, you know, if the casting person is saying

01:38:59.680 --> 01:39:04.880
[Guest 2]: this, that, you know, they only see you as that character, it's going to be a lot more

01:39:04.880 --> 01:39:08.320
[Guest 2]: effort to break out of it, right? And you and you really want to, that's, that's really

01:39:08.320 --> 01:39:09.320
[Guest 2]: a huge endeavor.

01:39:09.320 --> 01:39:13.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I also found the role of Jagdeep Chandra really interesting, because you're,

01:39:13.840 --> 01:39:19.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, obviously, the brief of the role is this over the top, ebullient, enthusiastic

01:39:19.080 --> 01:39:24.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of guy and you played it so well, that is very easy for me to see why people would,

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:28.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, imagine that in real life, maybe he's the one. So are you going to do more

01:39:28.960 --> 01:39:33.920
[Amit Varma]: writing now? Because Banana Bread, which I'll of course, recommend to all my listeners and

01:39:33.920 --> 01:39:38.360
[Amit Varma]: reading from the show notes was such a wonderful little miniature with the two of you, you

01:39:38.360 --> 01:39:43.040
[Amit Varma]: know, one of the best users of the lockdown that I've seen among people that I know, are

01:39:43.040 --> 01:39:46.600
[Amit Varma]: you going to do more writing and, you know, even directing at some point, maybe?

01:39:46.600 --> 01:39:50.480
[Guest 2]: Writing? Yes. I'm so I mean, I think Banana Bread has been a shot in the arm in that sense.

01:39:50.480 --> 01:39:55.520
[Guest 2]: I mean, it's given a lot of confidence. And I'm actually, we're actually working on something,

01:39:55.520 --> 01:39:58.520
[Guest 2]: I don't want to say too much to jinx it, but we're trying to work on another project to

01:39:58.520 --> 01:40:04.000
[Guest 2]: write something. So, you know, I, like I said earlier, I've always wanted to do more writing.

01:40:04.000 --> 01:40:09.160
[Guest 2]: The only scope I got of it was some storytelling that I did live storytelling, you know, so

01:40:09.160 --> 01:40:14.080
[Guest 2]: you have to craft your own piece and perform it, which I've done four or five stories.

01:40:14.080 --> 01:40:17.320
[Guest 2]: But now, yeah, I think I'm feeling a little encouraged because of Banana Bread and it's

01:40:17.320 --> 01:40:21.480
[Guest 2]: a bit of a push. So I do want to push on that front for sure. Direction, I don't know, it

01:40:21.480 --> 01:40:25.560
[Guest 2]: may be, you know, maybe later in the future, who knows, but right now, it's not a plan.

01:40:25.560 --> 01:40:29.920
[Amit Varma]: But I think definitely, hopefully. And so I've taken up a lot of your time, I'll just

01:40:29.920 --> 01:40:36.120
[Amit Varma]: ask a couple of more questions to both of you, one more general and one sort of about

01:40:36.120 --> 01:40:40.800
[Amit Varma]: your personal journeys. And the general one is that, you know, in a sense, we are, we've

01:40:40.800 --> 01:40:45.000
[Amit Varma]: lived through a very transformative period in Indian cinema and Indian entertainment

01:40:45.000 --> 01:40:49.160
[Amit Varma]: the last 20-30 years, just in terms of the way the world has opened up the role that

01:40:49.160 --> 01:40:54.320
[Amit Varma]: technology has played, all of that. It's so exciting. And you and as the formats are changing,

01:40:54.320 --> 01:41:00.080
[Amit Varma]: you also find that storytelling is evolving, the art is going to different places. What

01:41:00.080 --> 01:41:05.360
[Amit Varma]: are in general, when you look at this journey, and when you see how it's going, I mean, you

01:41:05.360 --> 01:41:10.640
[Amit Varma]: know, where do you kind of see this progression going? Like, is there a trap that eventually,

01:41:10.640 --> 01:41:16.120
[Amit Varma]: you know, more formulas will come out of it? And what is now a loosely forming ecosystem

01:41:16.120 --> 01:41:21.000
[Amit Varma]: will get ossified in its ways. And again, you'll have these big players and these massive

01:41:21.000 --> 01:41:25.920
[Amit Varma]: strugglers or, you know, what is your sort of view of all of this? Because you've actually

01:41:25.920 --> 01:41:30.560
[Amit Varma]: been participants in this whole process over the last decade or so.

01:41:30.560 --> 01:41:39.000
[Guest 1]: I'm not sure. I hope it remains as it is today. Because I think the big problem that I was

01:41:39.000 --> 01:41:47.600
[Guest 1]: facing before the OTT space boom was the problem of distribution and distribution remained

01:41:47.600 --> 01:41:52.920
[Guest 1]: the bottleneck for a very long time, especially in the kind of films that I was working in,

01:41:52.920 --> 01:41:58.960
[Guest 1]: like the example of Kisa, releasing only in two theatres. So I think technology had moved

01:41:58.960 --> 01:42:06.640
[Guest 1]: at that time, such that producing a film had become much cheaper, because things had moved

01:42:06.640 --> 01:42:12.480
[Guest 1]: from film film to cameras were digital. So the cost of production had fallen significantly.

01:42:12.480 --> 01:42:17.560
[Guest 1]: Also, a lot of one crore films that had reasonable success at that time, films like Beja Fry,

01:42:17.560 --> 01:42:24.640
[Guest 1]: had started a kind of trend. So when I joined, when I started acting, when I moved to Bombay,

01:42:24.640 --> 01:42:29.600
[Guest 1]: there was a whole period which initially was encouraging that a lot of production houses

01:42:29.600 --> 01:42:35.680
[Guest 1]: were producing smaller films, a lot of smaller production houses were springing up, but distribution

01:42:35.680 --> 01:42:39.920
[Guest 1]: remained a bottleneck for a very long time. And I think it took a year or two for everybody

01:42:39.920 --> 01:42:45.080
[Guest 1]: to realize, you know, we are producing all this great content, but we're not being able

01:42:45.080 --> 01:42:55.480
[Guest 1]: to find ways to distribute it. And then the OTT space happened. And I think that it has,

01:42:55.480 --> 01:43:02.920
[Guest 1]: for the last three, four years, been still democratic, still not releasing numbers, still

01:43:02.920 --> 01:43:09.480
[Guest 1]: encouraging newness, because I feel like a lot of actors became, quote unquote, successful

01:43:09.480 --> 01:43:13.640
[Guest 1]: in the early phase of the OTT space. But now still, there are different actors who are

01:43:13.640 --> 01:43:18.520
[Guest 1]: coming in every day, actors, directors, writers with new shows, which are becoming successful.

01:43:18.520 --> 01:43:23.560
[Guest 1]: So it's not like there's no room for newness. And there seems to be still room for newness,

01:43:23.560 --> 01:43:31.680
[Guest 1]: which I think is healthy. So I hope that that lasts. I'm not sure. But you know, recently,

01:43:31.680 --> 01:43:38.680
[Guest 1]: some platforms have started releasing numbers in some ways, and I'm very, very wary of that.

01:43:38.680 --> 01:43:43.680
[Guest 2]: So I hope that that doesn't happen. Yeah, I think, you know, in a lot of ways, we're

01:43:43.680 --> 01:43:47.640
[Guest 2]: really lucky. I mean, for all that, you know, you mentioned earlier that, you know, going

01:43:47.640 --> 01:43:52.760
[Guest 2]: through periods of self doubt and all that, you suddenly find yourself in that zone where

01:43:52.760 --> 01:43:56.920
[Guest 2]: there's a gold rush right now. And it's wonderful to be a part of the generation that's in the

01:43:56.920 --> 01:44:01.200
[Guest 2]: gold rush, because it's really a benefit to you. And even if this were to die down at

01:44:01.200 --> 01:44:05.920
[Guest 2]: some point in time, or the boom sort of reduces in size to some extent, hopefully, you've

01:44:05.920 --> 01:44:09.560
[Guest 2]: done some work that you know, people recognize you and you've got an opportunity to do it,

01:44:09.560 --> 01:44:13.920
[Guest 2]: which doesn't happen. I like what Rasika says. I mean, the distribution was this big bottleneck

01:44:13.920 --> 01:44:19.000
[Guest 2]: earlier. You know, like another film I did, Gurgaon, I remember, it got such few screens

01:44:19.000 --> 01:44:23.360
[Guest 2]: in the theaters, that my parents wanted to see it. And they're a very biased audience,

01:44:23.360 --> 01:44:28.200
[Guest 2]: right? They want to go and see it. And they couldn't because, you know, they weren't screens

01:44:28.200 --> 01:44:32.400
[Guest 2]: near their house at convenient times. It was, you know, it was just that tells you what

01:44:32.400 --> 01:44:37.400
[Guest 2]: kind of problems there were, right? You could make a film, but you couldn't distribute it.

01:44:37.400 --> 01:44:41.440
[Guest 2]: Now that distribution sort of those gateways have opened because you don't not just have

01:44:41.440 --> 01:44:46.400
[Guest 2]: the OTT, but you have many OTT platforms. And I think you have them because everybody

01:44:46.400 --> 01:44:50.200
[Guest 2]: is sort of trying to grab market share and go for it. There may come a time and this

01:44:50.200 --> 01:44:53.760
[Guest 2]: is my fear, because I'm always the pessimist who thinks about what the problems down the

01:44:53.760 --> 01:44:59.760
[Guest 2]: road are. But my fear is that if you again get to a point where there are only two or

01:44:59.760 --> 01:45:04.200
[Guest 2]: three OTT platforms and you have a different oligopoly now, you have, you know, Cartel,

01:45:04.200 --> 01:45:09.800
[Guest 2]: that was your cinema theater distribution chains. Now it goes to only two OTT platforms.

01:45:09.800 --> 01:45:13.080
[Guest 2]: You can have the same problem where they will just sort of command, you know, what work

01:45:13.080 --> 01:45:17.240
[Guest 2]: they want seen. And, you know, the terms of trade just changed completely towards them.

01:45:17.240 --> 01:45:21.720
[Guest 2]: So that's a fear that I have that that may happen. I hope that doesn't happen. I hope

01:45:21.720 --> 01:45:27.960
[Guest 2]: you do have, you know, a more even playing field where you had many, many more platforms

01:45:27.960 --> 01:45:32.200
[Guest 2]: because that allows for then, you know, proper competition. And that's good. The thing I'm

01:45:32.200 --> 01:45:37.600
[Guest 2]: hopeful of is that, you know, because data has become so cheap in India, that's a big

01:45:37.600 --> 01:45:42.520
[Guest 2]: part of what is happening. I mean, you know, we always wondered, you know, why people watch

01:45:42.520 --> 01:45:47.080
[Guest 2]: what is coming on general entertainment, television shows, and we thought it will never change.

01:45:47.080 --> 01:45:51.480
[Guest 2]: And now suddenly, you know, it's changing very fast. And I think it's also because people

01:45:51.480 --> 01:45:55.360
[Guest 2]: have access to a lot more shows. There's a lot more they can see, and then they will

01:45:55.360 --> 01:45:58.960
[Guest 2]: make that switch. So with data becoming cheap, and people are watching things across the

01:45:58.960 --> 01:46:03.960
[Guest 2]: world. I think that's great for all of us, because I find that true for me, I think,

01:46:03.960 --> 01:46:08.200
[Guest 2]: I think the quality of what, you know, even what actors are doing, what writers are doing,

01:46:08.200 --> 01:46:12.840
[Guest 2]: they, you know, they're raising the bar constantly, and you feel that pressure. And that's a good

01:46:12.840 --> 01:46:17.720
[Guest 2]: pressure that you just can't do what you were doing earlier, you know, people are people

01:46:17.720 --> 01:46:23.480
[Guest 2]: are pushing themselves to do better and better work. And I hope that that sort of global

01:46:23.480 --> 01:46:30.520
[Guest 2]: influence continues, because, you know, of technology enabling us to see a lot from everywhere.

01:46:30.520 --> 01:46:31.520
[Amit Varma]: And yeah,

01:46:31.520 --> 01:46:35.440
[Amit Varma]: yeah, I mean, just thinking aloud, it also strikes me that, you know, the bottleneck

01:46:35.440 --> 01:46:41.160
[Amit Varma]: has now shifted from distribution to our individual attentional capacity. And therefore, what

01:46:41.160 --> 01:46:45.520
[Amit Varma]: becomes important is what are the filters? How are you discovering content? And if those

01:46:45.520 --> 01:46:50.160
[Amit Varma]: filters are these mainstream filters, like you said, maybe, if they all consolidate into

01:46:50.160 --> 01:46:54.880
[Amit Varma]: two, three OTT platforms, then competition goes down, and you're not sort of serving

01:46:54.880 --> 01:46:59.600
[Amit Varma]: the long tail quite so well, though, your parents will still be able to log on to Netflix

01:46:59.600 --> 01:47:05.280
[Amit Varma]: and see your shows, I hope. And so I'm actually going to cheat. I said this, I had led you

01:47:05.280 --> 01:47:09.400
[Amit Varma]: to believe I'll have one question after this, but I thought of another one. So anyway, so

01:47:09.400 --> 01:47:14.840
[Amit Varma]: I'll throw in this extra one, which is that if there are aspiring young actors, or even

01:47:14.840 --> 01:47:19.280
[Amit Varma]: people who want to get into entertainment as directors or writers, whatever, but especially

01:47:19.280 --> 01:47:24.880
[Amit Varma]: actors, because, you know, that's what you guys have excelled at, what advice would you

01:47:24.880 --> 01:47:28.920
[Amit Varma]: give them not in terms of, you know, the kind of work they should do or whatever, because

01:47:28.920 --> 01:47:32.240
[Amit Varma]: that's really no one's control, but how should they approach all of this? How should they

01:47:32.240 --> 01:47:36.520
[Amit Varma]: look at it? Like, what advice would you give you guys give to a younger Mukul and Rasika

01:47:36.520 --> 01:47:41.040
[Amit Varma]: from 12 years ago, if you could, you know, send them a letter through a time machine?

01:47:41.040 --> 01:47:48.440
[Guest 1]: You know, anybody who tells me they want to become an actor, I say, please don't. It's

01:47:48.440 --> 01:47:55.840
[Guest 1]: a long process. And God knows what might happen. You know, there's no surety of where your

01:47:55.840 --> 01:48:00.840
[Guest 1]: career will go. And there's no one way of getting it right. And it's such a matter of

01:48:00.840 --> 01:48:06.640
[Guest 1]: chance that, and things have to just align in a certain way at a certain time. And you

01:48:06.640 --> 01:48:13.600
[Guest 1]: might be the most talented, most hardworking, good at networking, all of that. And you still

01:48:13.600 --> 01:48:19.680
[Guest 1]: might not be able to get the projects that get you more work or have a career, which

01:48:19.680 --> 01:48:25.240
[Guest 1]: is long and fulfilling, you know, so it's, it's so full of uncertainties that I feel

01:48:25.240 --> 01:48:31.040
[Guest 1]: very nervous every time anybody tells me that they want to become an actor. And I think

01:48:31.040 --> 01:48:35.680
[Guest 1]: if I thought things through, I wouldn't have, it would have been too scary. You know, but

01:48:35.680 --> 01:48:39.720
[Guest 1]: I just didn't think things through. I was just too enthusiastic about everything that

01:48:39.720 --> 01:48:44.200
[Amit Varma]: was coming my way. No, that's, that's really insightful. And it's, it's an illustration

01:48:44.200 --> 01:48:48.920
[Amit Varma]: of the survivorship bias, which is that you look at people at the top of a field and you

01:48:48.920 --> 01:48:52.800
[Amit Varma]: imagine that, oh, I'm going to be that person, but your probability of actually getting there

01:48:52.800 --> 01:48:57.880
[Amit Varma]: may be so ridiculously low, that is better not to do it at all, which is why I think

01:48:57.880 --> 01:49:01.920
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, that cliched advice with self help authors will sometimes give people a

01:49:01.920 --> 01:49:06.480
[Amit Varma]: follow your dreams can actually be very dangerous advice, because so many people who follow

01:49:06.480 --> 01:49:11.080
[Amit Varma]: their dreams, just completely fall apart. And maybe it's better just to do your degrees

01:49:11.080 --> 01:49:14.680
[Amit Varma]: and get all that into place. And that kind of middle class mentality, I can't, you know,

01:49:14.680 --> 01:49:20.960
[Amit Varma]: the 20 year old me heard me saying this today, he would be so horrified and shocked. Mukul,

01:49:20.960 --> 01:49:22.520
[Guest 2]: you have anything to sort of add to?

01:49:22.520 --> 01:49:26.160
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I just want to say like, like Raseka said, I think I didn't think it through entirely.

01:49:26.160 --> 01:49:30.000
[Guest 2]: Otherwise, I might not have been here. If I had been my pessimistic self and said, what

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:33.760
[Guest 2]: are the chances I have for any form of success, I would have very quickly said that, look,

01:49:33.760 --> 01:49:38.760
[Guest 2]: this is not working, you have to do something else. So I kind of have almost contradictory

01:49:38.760 --> 01:49:44.640
[Guest 2]: advice to a younger version of myself, because on the one hand, acting is such a success

01:49:44.640 --> 01:49:47.800
[Guest 2]: that it is so difficult that you have to play the long game, you have to just keep hanging

01:49:47.800 --> 01:49:52.360
[Guest 2]: in there. So that you know, something, it may just take his time, you never know when

01:49:52.360 --> 01:49:56.680
[Guest 2]: you get a break, or when something happens that allows you to get that validation and

01:49:56.680 --> 01:50:01.160
[Guest 2]: allows you to get more work and carry on, you can't obviously bet on some OTT revolution

01:50:01.160 --> 01:50:06.200
[Guest 2]: coming some years down the line. So I think to some extent, I might have survived also

01:50:06.200 --> 01:50:11.880
[Guest 2]: because I kind of did other things. On the other hand, my advice to myself is don't get

01:50:11.880 --> 01:50:15.240
[Guest 2]: distracted by doing other things. You know, I have some sense of focus, because I do feel

01:50:15.240 --> 01:50:19.600
[Guest 2]: that I did waste a lot of time and a number of years, because I was sort of dabbling in

01:50:19.600 --> 01:50:25.120
[Guest 2]: multiple things and not focused on one thing. So I don't know, it's a mix of the two. That

01:50:25.120 --> 01:50:29.040
[Guest 2]: you know, play the long game, but at the same time, I'm focused. But to your point that

01:50:29.040 --> 01:50:33.960
[Guest 2]: you know, don't, I'm always someone to advise people to take more risks in life, you know,

01:50:33.960 --> 01:50:38.360
[Amit Varma]: always take more risks, because I think it's the payoffs are much greater, the risk is

01:50:38.360 --> 01:50:41.840
[Guest 2]: higher, but the payoffs are so much greater. If it doesn't work, then you have to of course,

01:50:41.840 --> 01:50:45.520
[Guest 2]: the tough part is to have the ability to walk away at some point and then and then you know,

01:50:45.520 --> 01:50:49.640
[Guest 2]: try something else. But I think we don't take enough risk in life. And this could be a long

01:50:49.640 --> 01:50:54.600
[Guest 2]: philosophical discussion, which is kind of pointless. But I mean, it's been a fun journey.

01:50:54.600 --> 01:50:58.960
[Guest 2]: I don't have any regrets about it, despite the many ups and downs. And even if it turns

01:50:58.960 --> 01:51:02.080
[Guest 2]: out that, you know, four years later, I have to say that, you know, this is it, and I've

01:51:02.080 --> 01:51:05.640
[Guest 2]: got to do something else, or I choose to do something else. It's been a fun journey.

01:51:05.640 --> 01:51:10.160
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, you know, this adds a new dimension to something that I often say, where I'll

01:51:10.160 --> 01:51:14.880
[Amit Varma]: often tell people that self delusion is a prerequisite to success. And the sense that

01:51:14.880 --> 01:51:19.640
[Amit Varma]: I mean it in is that when you begin doing something, you're pretty bad at it, by definition,

01:51:19.640 --> 01:51:23.280
[Amit Varma]: because you have begun. And if you were to actually recognize how bad you are at it,

01:51:23.280 --> 01:51:26.760
[Amit Varma]: you would not do it at all, you would be so disheartened. But because you think you're

01:51:26.760 --> 01:51:31.000
[Amit Varma]: good, and you want to keep doing it, you just keep doing it, doing it, doing it, and endless

01:51:31.000 --> 01:51:35.320
[Amit Varma]: iterations in the 10,000 hours, and so on, eventually make you good at it. So you have

01:51:35.320 --> 01:51:39.440
[Amit Varma]: to be self delusional at the start. But the layer that you guys added to it is that the

01:51:39.440 --> 01:51:44.360
[Amit Varma]: probability of success is so incredibly low, that if we were clear sighted about that,

01:51:44.360 --> 01:51:49.280
[Amit Varma]: at the start, we might decide not to take the risk, no matter how great the payoff is.

01:51:49.280 --> 01:51:54.240
[Amit Varma]: But we overestimate our abilities and our chances. And therefore, we kind of go down

01:51:54.240 --> 01:51:58.240
[Amit Varma]: that road. My final question to you is, and you guys have been so patient, this is almost

01:51:58.240 --> 01:52:02.320
[Amit Varma]: this is actually longer than some films that you guys will make. So thank you so much for

01:52:02.320 --> 01:52:03.320
[Unknown]: doing this.

01:52:03.320 --> 01:52:04.320
[Unknown]: It's the OTT world now.

01:52:04.320 --> 01:52:10.080
[Amit Varma]: It's the OTT world now. Long form. So my final question to you guys is that in these incredibly

01:52:10.080 --> 01:52:14.160
[Amit Varma]: exciting times, and just as a consumer, I am excited. And I'm so excited for you guys

01:52:14.160 --> 01:52:17.840
[Amit Varma]: as well, because of the kind of work that's coming out. Where do you see yourself five

01:52:17.840 --> 01:52:22.080
[Amit Varma]: years from now? What are Mukul and Rasika doing five years from now, or even 10 years

01:52:22.080 --> 01:52:25.800
[Amit Varma]: from now, whatever you kind of prefer? Who are you five years from now? What is the kind

01:52:25.800 --> 01:52:29.920
[Amit Varma]: of work that you're doing in the sort of universe you're engrossed in the kind of roles that

01:52:29.920 --> 01:52:35.640
[Amit Varma]: are playing? Give me a sense of how you would like it to go? Let's, let's not end on possible

01:52:35.640 --> 01:52:38.840
[Guest 1]: notes of despair.

01:52:38.840 --> 01:52:45.280
[Guest 1]: I would like to be a part of, you know, like be involved in ideating a project, because

01:52:45.280 --> 01:52:51.160
[Guest 1]: that's something as an actor, I feel that I have very little agency, when I arrive to

01:52:51.160 --> 01:52:58.080
[Guest 1]: do my work, it's been written, which is half done. It's being visualized by somebody else.

01:52:58.080 --> 01:53:04.040
[Guest 1]: I don't want to be that somebody else visualizing it, it's too much responsibility to be a director,

01:53:04.040 --> 01:53:08.120
[Guest 1]: you have to have, I feel you have to be God to be a director, you know, you have to, you

01:53:08.120 --> 01:53:14.500
[Guest 1]: have to know everything and be a good manager and know exactly what works with somebody

01:53:14.500 --> 01:53:18.680
[Guest 1]: and what doesn't work with somebody else. It's, I don't know how people sign up for

01:53:18.680 --> 01:53:22.680
[Guest 1]: a job like that. It's very, very difficult. So I don't want to be that. But yeah, I'd

01:53:22.680 --> 01:53:28.720
[Guest 1]: like to put a project together and be involved in it from the initiation of it, stories that

01:53:28.720 --> 01:53:34.760
[Guest 1]: I'm interested in telling and being a part of as an actor. Also, really, I'm very interested

01:53:34.760 --> 01:53:41.600
[Guest 1]: in doing some international work. So if I can sort of expand to that, I would feel very

01:53:41.600 --> 01:53:48.560
[Guest 1]: happy. Because I feel that I've been taken in by many actors and shows and films that

01:53:48.560 --> 01:53:56.800
[Guest 1]: I've seen in Hollywood. And that's been interesting to me. And I would I wonder how it would be

01:53:56.800 --> 01:54:02.880
[Guest 1]: to work in another culture as an actor, you know, that there would be an added layer of

01:54:02.880 --> 01:54:06.920
[Guest 1]: vulnerability there. So I think that would be interesting.

01:54:06.920 --> 01:54:12.240
[Guest 2]: I think where I stand right now, so what I'm, I would like to do as much varied work as

01:54:12.240 --> 01:54:16.040
[Guest 2]: possible play as many varied characters as possible. And I think that maybe comes from

01:54:16.040 --> 01:54:20.120
[Guest 2]: the earlier statement of having felt this pressure of being typecast, but I really would

01:54:20.120 --> 01:54:24.120
[Guest 2]: want to do as many things. And you know, you talked about self delusion, I think actors

01:54:24.120 --> 01:54:28.280
[Guest 2]: are particularly delusional about themselves, because we believe that we can play any part

01:54:28.280 --> 01:54:32.240
[Guest 2]: out there. I mean, somebody's grandmother's role, I play that no problem, I believe I

